<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Urges Washington Full Compliance With Nuclear Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) Friday urged Washington to fulfill its obligations
of an agreement under which Pyongyang froze its suspected nuclear
program.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the Korea Central News Agency, a
Foreign Ministry spokesman said, "the U.S. has not taken
substantial measures to ease its sanctions but made empty talk for
years."
</P>
<P>
"And it (Washington) has made little progress in the
construction of light-water reactors (LWRs) under the pretext of
internal problems ... though it is more than two years since the
LWR supply agreement was adopted," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot but express deep concern over this insincere
attitude of the US toward the implementation of the framework
agreement," he added.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK signed a framework agreement with the United States in
1994, promising to freeze its nuclear plant. In return, Washington
agreed to ease its trade sanctions against Pyongyang and arrange
for international financing and supply of two modern reactors.
</P>
<P>
"We lost no time to freeze our independent nuclear power
facilities we had built with colossal funds and labor. We are
promoting the safe storage of spent fuel in the final stage."
</P>
<P>
"Thus, we have sincerely fulfilled our obligations under the
agreement, which the U.S. administration has officially confirmed,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said U.S. fulfillment of its side of the agreement
was "lagging behind our sincere efforts."
</P>
<P>
"It does not make any sense to victimize our independent
nuclear power industry continuously with hopes pinned on the
light-water reactors that are not sure to come."
</P>
<P>
"Nobody can predict what will happen unless the US seeks new
practical measures and takes decisive action to implement its
obligations under the agreement as scheduled," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
