<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Turkish Cypriots' Cooperation on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) External
Relations Commissioner Hans Van den Broek Friday called on the
Turkish Cypriots to look toward future in dealing with the Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the end of his two-day visit
to the island, Van den Broek described his visit not as a big
breakthrough but as a preparation for the opening of Cyprus-EU
accession negotiations, due to start on March 31.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek said he held useful talks with President Glafcos
Clerides, Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides and George
Vassiliou who will head the Republic's negotiating team.
</P>
<P>
However, the EU official expressed regret for Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash's refusal to meet with him.
</P>
<P>
Denktash turned down a request by the EU official for a
meeting in protest against the EU's decision to start accession
talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek said he was encouraged by the fact that the
Cypriot government "is very much dedicated and seriously
considers how the interests of Turkish Cypriots can also be
respected in the arrangements for negotiations."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out, however, that Turkish Cypriot cooperation is
much required, expressing the hope that "Turkish Cypriots will not
concentrate on the present and the past but look clearly also
toward the future."
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek said the Turkish Cypriot community will gain much
if a federal Cyprus enters the EU.
</P>
<P>
"I continue to hope that the Turkish Cypriot community will
also be able to accept that a common future (with the Greek
community) is a better solution than a separate one in relative
isolation," the EU official said.
</P>
<P>
The EU believes that Cyprus' membership would help reunify the
island and wants the Turkish Cypriots to participate in the
accession talks.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek also reaffirmed that the EU will not recognize
the breakaway state unilaterally declared in 1983 by the Turkish
Cypriots in the northern Cyprus, which was only recognized by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Turkey's attitude toward the EU, Van den Broek
said Turkey remains a key partner for political and economic
reasons and for reasons of good neighborly relations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the EU regrets the interruption in its dialog
with Turkey resulted from Ankara's anger over EU's selection of
Cyprus as accession candidate. He expressed the hope it will only
be temporary, pointing out that a development in relations with
Turkey could have a certain impact and reflection on the attitude
of the Turkish Cypriot community.
</P>
<P>
British envoy for Cyprus and representative of the EU
presidency David Hannay accompanied Van den Broek for the visit to
the island.
</P>
<P>
Hannay has said that Cyprus' EU membership negotiations can
start without the Turkish Cypriots, but cannot be conducted
without them.
</P>
<P>
Denktash and Turkey reject Cyprus' accession before Turkey
itself joins the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
