<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian Army on High Alert on Yugoslav Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Defense Minister Sabit
Brokaj said Thursday that military forces stationed in the
country's northern part bordering Yugoslavia have been on high
alert to deal with any contingency in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Brokaj, as quoted by media reports here, made the remarks when
addressing inquiries to the People's Assembly, or parliament,
Thursday evening as a response to the recent escalated ethnic
violence in Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Tension heightened in Kosovo last weekend after a Serbian
police patrol and local ethnic Albanians, who account for 90
percent of the regional population, engaged in a fierce cross-fire
that killed four policemen and 16 Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister said Albanian troops have prepared for a
further escalation of the conflict, but denied any more military
movement to the border region at the present time.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Interior Minister Neritan Ceka
pledged to the parliament that Albania's frontier forces have been
ready to handle the situation.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony for the reopening of a copper mill on Thursday,
Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano said his government would
"stand together with brothers in Kosovo, ready at all times to
help them carry out their justified national aspirations."
</P>
<P>
The Albanian parliament, however, ruled out the possibility of
military intervention into the Kosovo conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
