<HEADLINE> Russia Outraged at Latvia's Allegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin Friday strongly denounced his Latvian counterpart
Guntars Krasts's allegation that Moscow was involved in
Russian-speakers' protest action in Riga, the capital of Latvia.
</P>
<P>
"How is it possible to go to such lengths as to claim that
Russia allegedly put pensioners on the picket line," said
Chernomyrdin, extremely indignant at the statement.
</P>
<P>
With such premiers like Krasts, said the Russian prime
minister, the relations between Russian and Latvia can degenerate
into very dramatic developments.
</P>
<P>
"It is inadmissible to trample underfoot human rights in Europe
at the end of the 20th century. There is no justification for
this," Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
Krasts has stated that "the picket of pensioners outside the
Riga Duma on March 3 might be a Russian provocation," an Itar-Tass
news agency report said earlier.
</P>
<P>
The problem of the right and status of the Russian-speakers
remains key obstacle in the growth of relations between Russia and
Latvia since the Baltic state gained independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
There are some 700,000 Russian-speakers in Latvia, among them
only 4,500 have been given the Latvian citizenship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
