<HEADLINE> CIS Members Sign 11 Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Prime ministers of the Commonwealth
of Independent States (CIS) signed 11 agreements here Friday to
promote cooperation within the bloc, reported Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
Signed at a day-long session of the CIS Council of Heads of
Governments, the documents call for transnational corporations, a
common CIS agricultural market and cooperation in military and
judicial affairs.
</P>
<P>
However, a few documents failed to get unanimously signed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the end of the assembly, Russian Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin urged the CIS members to speed up the building
of a free trade zone within the framework of the commonwealth to
deepen and develop their contacts.
</P>
<P>
He called on removing all artificial barriers and developing
all that promotes integration of the organization.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin pointed out the fact that Russia's trade turnover
with other CIS members totalled 30 billion U.S. dollars last year
proves that "We need each other."
</P>
<P>
The 12-member CIS, which is composed of all the former Soviet
republics except the three Baltic nations, was established in 1991
following the break-up of the former Soviet Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
