<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Calls for New Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot Leader Rauf
Denktash Friday called on Cyprus' re-elected President Glafcos
Clerides to cooperate in creating a new Cyprus based on the
existence of two sovereign states.
</P>
<P>
In a letter from Denktash to Clerides, a copy of which was
faxed to Xinhua, Denktash laid down three main criteria for a
reconciliation on Cyprus: to delineate the boundaries, to settle
the exchange of property and security matters.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Denktash said "I am convinced that the best way
to build a better future is first to reach a common understanding
on the guiding principles which will shape that future."
</P>
<P>
"The fundamental point in the circumstances of Cyprus is
clearly the sovereign equality of the two sides based on the
principles of symmetry and mutual respect," added the Turkish
Cypriot leader.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops landed and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. The Turkish
Cypriots declared a breakaway republic in norther Cyprus in 1983,
which was only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has maintained about 35,000 troops to protect the
minority Turkish Cypriots in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Denktash pointed out that neither Turkish Cypriots nor Greek
Cypriots have exclusive rights over the independence and
sovereignty of Cyprus and the balance established between Turkey
and Greece has to be respected and preserved.
</P>
<P>
Denktash stressed that "efforts to build a worthwhile future
for both our peoples must therefore be based on the acknowledgment
of the existence and equal status of our respective states."
</P>
<P>
"What needs to be done now is to work out an arrangement which
will enable the two states to resolve certain basic matters,
specifically the final settlement of reciprocal property claims,
security issues and the delineation of borders," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The time has come for both of us to show the necessary
leadership so that the future generations do not bare the bitter
experiences that both you and I have endured," said Denktash in
the letter.
</P>
<P>
He added "our primary aim must be the immediate achievement of
a working relationship between our two states so that peace,
stability and mutual trust can be secured and the danger of a new
conflict is averted." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
