<HEADLINE> German FM Calls for UN Security Council Debate on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 6 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
today called on the United Nations Security Council to hold an
urgent meeting to seek measures to stem further escalation of
violent conflicts in the Kosovo region of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Describing the situation in Kosovo as "highly explosive",
Kinkel also urged the UN to extend its military presence in the
Republic of Macedonia which borders Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
must also employ all available instruments of preventive
diplomacy, including sending its special envoy Felipe Gonzales of
Spain again to Kosovo and an expansion of the OSCE peace mission
in Albania and the Republic of Mazedonia.
</P>
<P>
The German foreign minister also called for an immediate
meeting of foreign ministers of the region with the international
contact group consisting of the United States, Russia, France,
Britain, Germany and Italy in a bid to seek coordinated actions in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Germany had a special interest to seek a solution to the Kosovo
crisis because of the presence of about 140,000 Kosovo-Albanian
refugees in Germany, Kinkel stressed.
</P>
<P>
"what is extremely necessary now is the beginning of a dialogue
between Belgrade and the ethnic Albanian majority in Kosovo about
the future of the Serbian province," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also repeated his warning on Thursday that "Belgrade's
return ticket to Europe is dependent on its attitude on the Kosovo
issue".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Kinkel also warned militant Kosovo-Albanians to stop
terrorist activities, stressing that terrorism, provocation and
violence would not serve their cause and would not be tolerated by
the international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
