<HEADLINE> Kohl Voices Growing Concern about Standstill in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 6 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today
voiced at a meeting with visiting Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu his "growing concern" about the current standstill in
the Middle East peace process and called on Israeli and
Palestinian leaders to use every chance for dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is on a four-day European tour to seek support for
his proposal to hold a new international conference on the Middle
East peace which he said would pave the way for new negotiations
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He announced such a proposal Thursday in Madrid, the first stop
of his European tour which will also bring him to London and Oslo.
</P>
<P>
According to German government spokesman Peter Hausmann, Kohl
called on Israeli and Palestinian leaders to achieve "substantial
and constructive progress" especially in such key areas as
security, Israel's activities to build Jewish settlements and its
troop withdrawal from occupies territories.
</P>
<P>
Kohl also stressed that Germany, along with its European
partners, would continue to bring "energetic support" to the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
In interviews with Spanish media on Thursday, Netanyahu also
talked of a proposal to replace Israeli troops in South Lebanon
with international troops. However, there was no confirmation in
Bonn whether Netanyahu had informed Kohl of such a plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
