<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Building Permits Value Down in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The value of building permits
declined in January in Canada, due in part to the ice storm in
central and eastern parts of the country, Statistics Canada
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Overall, municipalities issued 2.6 billion dollars (1.8 billion
USD) building permits, down 9.9 percent from December, the
statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Of these, non-residential construction intentions declined 19.5
percent to 1.1 billion dollars, while home building intentions
fell 1.3 percent to 1.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Municipal services, including those for building permits, were
severely curtailed because of the ice storm that knocked out power
supplies to Montreal, eastern Ontario and part of the Maritimes.
</P>
<P>
The value of permits were down 21.0 percent in Quebec, and 6.0
percent in Ontario.
</P>
<P>
Even so, the total value of building permits issued across the
country was still 8.7 percent higher than the same month in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
