<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Registers Robust Job growth in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States registered a
robust job growth in February, bringing down the nation's
unemployment rate to a 24-year low of 4.6 percent, the Labor
Department said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted unemployment rate declined from 4.7
percent in January and December and matched November's 4.6 percent
rate, which was the lowest since October 1973, according to the
department.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to a drop in mortgage rates, to a four-year low of just
under 7 percent, there has been increased demand for new homes.
Employers created a greater-than-expected 310,000 jobs, on top of
375,000 in January. That included 41,000 new construction jobs and
17,000 jobs in the finance industry.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the severe rain and ice storms in some parts of the
country have stimulated hiring for cleanup and rebuilding, and
this winter's weather has been generally mild in many parts of the
country to allow the continuation of construction activity that
ordinarily would have been curtailed, as an analyst put it.
</P>
<P>
Other areas of strong growth included temporary help firms,
52,000 jobs; computer and data processing, 20,000; health
services, 25,000; government, 36,000, and transportation, 34,000,
mostly at airlines and trucking firms.
</P>
<P>
Retailing added a relatively mild 15,000 jobs and payrolls
declined by 2,000 jobs in both mining and manufacturing. It was
the first drop in manufacturing in five months and may reflect
reduced import demand for Asian countries suffering from financial
instability.
</P>
<P>
It was noticed that the Asian crisis seems to have helped the
U.S. job market by pushing interest rates down. The percentage of
adults with jobs, 64.2 percent, which was at an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
Average hourly wages increased a robust 0.6 percent to 12.60
U.S. dollars, which is up 4.1 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
By demographic group, the unemployment rate was 3.8 percent for
adult men, 4.3 percent for adult women, 14.7 percent for
teen-agers, 3.9 percent for whites, 9.7 percent for Hispanics and
6.8 percent for Hispanics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
