<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland's Jobless Rate Falls to 7-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Ireland's unemployment rate fell to
the rate of 9.6 percent in February, marking a seven year low in
adjusted terms, according to press reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
The Central Statistics Office announced earlier Friday that the
number of people claiming unemployment benefit in Republic of
Ireland had dropped to a seasonally adjusted 238,000 in February,
a seven year low.
</P>
<P>
That implied a standardised unemployment rate of 9.6 percent
for Ireland, down from 9.7 percent in January and below the 10.2
percent average in 1997, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the encouraging jobless figure, Irish Deputy
Prime Minister Mary Harney said: "Ireland's unemployment rate is
below that of the economic powerhouse of the EU, Germany. That is
certainly something that should be posted on the worldwide web
today."
</P>
<P>
Harney stressed that the latest figure underpinned her belief
that unemployment in Ireland could realistically be halved over
the next five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
