<HEADLINE> Mugabe Calls on Zimbabwean People to Unite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Friday urged the people to unite and to guard against being used
by white racists, the Zimbabwean News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an rally in Hurungwe of northwest Zimbabwe, Mugabe
said: "Some members of parliament elected on a party ticket are
now saying the ruling party has overstayed in the government and
that Mugabe should step down as president."
</P>
<P>
"Look out for those people who speak ill of the party because
they are being used by white racists," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there is in-house and factional fighting in the ruling
ZANU (PF) because people are being used by disgruntled white
farmers whose land is designated and business people opposed to
ZANU (PF) rule.
</P>
<P>
Land, he said, should be given to the people and those against
this are fighting the party, adding that all land taken from the
whites should be redistributed leaving them with just enough.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe also took a swipe at the foreign press, newspapers and
radio stations which now portray him as anti-white for
designating land and redistributing it to the black majority.
</P>
<P>
Those given land should ensure that agriculture continues to
flourish to confound critics such as the Commercial Farmers Union
which seems to think blacks cannot grow maize, soyabeans and
cotton on a commercial basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that to ensure success of the blacks, there is need
for support in the form of fertilizers, seed and tractors, but
not knowledge because blacks had already shown to have it.
</P>
</TEXT>
