<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardiovascular Drugs Linked to Suicide Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Some drugs used to treat heart
problems may increase the risk of depression and suicide,
researchers said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Doctors in Sweden have found a significant correlation between
the use of calcium channel blockers, a relatively new class of
drug prescribed for angina and high blood pressure, and the
incidence of suicide.
</P>
<P>
The research team, led by Dr Anne Melander at Malmo University
Hospital in Sweden, surveyed 152 Swedish municipalities with a
total population of 7.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
In a separate part of the study, the researchers found a
five-fold increase in suicides among those taking calcium channel
blockers compared with users of other anti-hypertensives.
</P>
<P>
"Calcium channel blockers should be considered a possible cause
of depression and suicide." they concluded in the British Medical
Journal.
</P>
<P>
The authors suggested that the drugs may interfere with
neurones and other mechanisms which affect moods and emotions.
They called for further investigations into the effects of calcium
channel blockers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
