<HEADLINE> Malawian Kwacha's Devaluation Troubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Malawian Kwacha's devaluation of
about 60 percent due to the scarcity of foreign exchange in the
country's currency market continues to trouble local businessmen
Thursday, Zambia News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The scarcity of foreign exchange in the past weeks has pushed
down the Kwacha from 15 to 24.26 against the U.S. Dollar,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a businessman as saying that "to get travellers'
cheque has even become difficult and three weeks now I have been
waiting to go to South Africa but my bank says it has no foreign
currency."
</P>
<P>
The scarcity has been brought about by the central
government's over-expenditure. The result, eonomists say, is that
the measure put some brake on the country's in-flows of the much
needed foreign aid sued in balance of payments support.
</P>
<P>
A team from the International Monetary Fund arrived in Malawi
last week for discussions with Malawian officials on the current
economic situation, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The team, which once went to Malawi last November, is to
review government's measures to redress the weak areas of its
economic management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
