<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe's Last Tin Mine Ceases Work in England </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Europe's last tin mine, South
Crofty pit in the county of Cornwall in western England, closed
Friday, ending 4,000 years of production in the area, according to
a BBC television report Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cheaper tin production in Latin America's Bolivia and Brazil
has been blamed for the closure of the mine.
</P>
<P>
This means the loss of 200 jobs and marks the end of a long
mining tradition in southwest England.
</P>
<P>
"It's the end of a way of life. There's not a lot of prospects
for us around here," said mine captain Paul Bray.
</P>
<P>
However, union officials insist that the mine is still a viable
business.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the mine's days have been numbered since
the UK government turned down a request from its owners for a 5.9
million pounds (9.6 million US dollars) subsidy to see it through
a period of low tin prices.
</P>
<P>
The heyday of South Crofty pit, a small mine which produced
2,100 tons of tin in 1996, came during the industrial revolution
of the 19th century, and in the 1850s and 1860s there were some 50
pits in Cornwall, and the county produced most of the world's
copper and tin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
