<HEADLINE> 6,000 UNITA Soldiers Not yet Demobilized in Central Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The opposition National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) still has 6,000 armed
soldiers in central Angola, the Angola News Agency reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Angolan military sources as saying that the
6,000 UNITA soldiers stationed in Huambo, Bie and Kuanza-Sul
provinces have not been demobilized. And the UNITA leader Jonas
Savimbi also has an additional guard of 2,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The 6,000 UNITA soldiers are divided into seven battalions,
out of which five battalions under the command of UNITA General
Cassessa are operating in the border areas of Huambo and Bie
provinces, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The other two battalions are operating in the diamond areas of
Bie Province, some areas of Bemguela Province and Kuanza-Sul
Province.
</P>
<P>
These UNITA soldiers in plain clothes and with hidden weapons
are not easy to identify, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the remanent UNITA soldiers are
seriously threatening the peace process in Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
