<HEADLINE> Mozambican Government Willing to Dialogue with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal
Mocumbi said here Friday that his government is "always willing
to hold dialogue with the opposition" to discuss issues related
with local elections.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made the remarks at a news conference held
in Maputo, adding that "we have never refused to have dialogue
with any party".
</P>
<P>
But he said that the government has not officially received
any request from the opposition to hold a meeting together.
</P>
<P>
Local elections are due to take place on May 29 in 33 cities
and towns of Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, some opposition parties and coalitions indicated
at a news conference that whether they will take part in local
elections depends on "an important meeting" with the government,
which aims at seeking ways of rectifying deviations in the voter
registration at the end of last year. 
