<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-fox Hunting Bill in UK Set for Failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A bid to ban fox hunting in Britain
looks doomed to failure on Friday after making little headway in
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Despite a five-hour debate, only one of 13 groups of amendments
to the bill, piloted by Labor MP Mike Foster, had been completed
by the close of the session.
</P>
<P>
The MPs campaigning to ban fox-hunting accused their opponents
of using disgraceful delaying tactics to stop their bill becoming
law.
</P>
<P>
The bill to ban fox hunting is bitterly opposed in the
countryside, and about 250,000 rural people marched through London
last week to protest against what they see as a growing threat to
their way of life.
</P>
<P>
Although Prime Minister Tony Blair has expressed sympathy for
the goal of the bill, he is reluctant to antagonise an
increasingly vocal countryside lobby.
</P>
<P>
Animal rights activists presented a one million signature
petition in favour of the bill, which would outlaw hunting with
hounds, to Prime Minister Tony Blair on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Its advocates had hoped the government would either provide
more debating time or allow an amendment to outlaw hunting to be
added to a Criminal Justice Bill it is to present to Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The bill is to be discussed for a further five hours next
Friday, but it is almost certain then to be abandoned because no
further time is available for debate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Imports Fertilizer for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian government has
imported 368,000 tons of fertilizer for 1998 production year, the
National Fertilizer Industry Agency of Ethiopia has announced.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing here Friday, General Manager of the agency
Zeleke Desalegne said that fertilizer whole-sale price
deregulation issued recently by the government facilitates the
sale of fertilizer to the peasant at a reasonable price.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government decided to lift the regulation on
fertilizer price aiming mainly at enhancing free fertilizer trade
actively across the nation, saying that the newly introduced
system creates a fertile ground for fertilizer suppliers to carry
out their activity freely and effectively in all parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
According to the general manager, the consumption of
fertilizer in Ethiopia has increased significantly over the past
few years following the expansion of the extension program and
the rising awareness of the peasant about the advantages of
applying the item.
</P>
<P>
The general manager said, the Ethiopian government has also
devised mechanisms to closely inspect the proper distribution of
quality fertilizer to the peasant this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
