Friday reiterated his country's commitment to international
peace-keeping assignments within the framework of the United
Nations and the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
Addressing about 500 Zimbabwean soldiers just-returned from
peacekeeping duties in Angola, Mugabe said as a member of the U.N.
and the OAU, Zimbabwe would assist, wherever possible, to solve
the pervasive problems of conflict.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when welcoming the troops at Magunje, 200
km northwest of Harare, according to the Zimbabwe News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean president also prayed for durable peace in
Angola, the war-ravaged southern African country, which is
teetering on the brink of renewed war again as U.N. peace keepers
pull out at the end of their mandate.
</P>
<P>
"With the U.N. mandate in Angola having effectively ended on
January 21, 1998, it is our sincere hope that peace will prevail
permanently and thus no loss of innocent lives and destruction of
property will any longer be experienced in that country," said
he.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who is chairman of the OAU Ad Hoc Committee on Angola,
said this at a time the peace process wound up but with clouds of
war still hovering in the Angolan skies. 
</P>
