<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ambassador Shen: Sanctions against Libya Should be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The sanctions against Libya
should be lifted as soon as possible, Chinese Deputy Permanent
Representative to the United Nations Shen Guofeng stressed on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Shen made the remarks after the United Nations
Security Council finished its informal consultations on the issue
of Libya in which no agreement was reached on lifting the
sanctions against the country.
</P>
<P>
"Today the Security Council came back once again to review
sanctions on Libya. Regrettably, no consensus was reached. We
hope all parties concerned could show some flexibility and the
Council can take a step forward in this issue," Shen said.
</P>
<P>
"China does not favor any kind of sanction against any country
including sanctions on Libya. So we support the request by the
Arab League and the Organization of African Unity for an early
lifting of the sanctions," Shen said.
</P>
<P>
"Facts have proved that such sanctions instead of doing any
good to the settlement of the issue have the potential of further
intensifying the conflict. Sanctions have not only brought
sufferings to its people, but also undermine the economic and
social development of the country. These sanctions have had
harmful impact on third countries too," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"The key to solve the Lockerbie case is for parties concerned
to reach an agreement as soon as possible on where and how the
trial of the two suspects should be held. We are of the view that
the three options put forward by the Arab League and the
Organization of African Unity are constructive and should be
supported. We are also in favor of an open debate on the Libya
issue as soon as possible," Shen added.
</P>
<P>
Libya has been under sanctions since 1992 for failing to hand
over two suspects in the 1988 mid-air bombing of a Pan American
airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, which killed 270 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
