<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fuel Prices Readjusted in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Prices of liquid fuel in
Mozambique is readjusted Friday, with lighting oil and Jet A1
prices reduced to a large extent while prices for gas and fuel
oil up a bit.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release issued here Friday by the Ministry
of Mineral Resources and Energy, lighting oil is now sold at
2,250 Meticais (about 19 U.S. cents) per liter, 29 percent lower,
while Jet A1 is reduced by 25.8 percent at 2,688 Meticais (23
U.S. cents) per liter.
</P>
<P>
The prices for petroleum and diesel oil are down by three
percent and 8.3 percent respectively, at 56 cents and 41 cents
approximately per liter.
</P>
<P>
Gas and fuel oil are up by 1.7 percent and 4.3 percent
respectively, at about 57 cents and 21 cents per liter.
</P>
<P>
The prices are the highest allowed for the capital Maputo,
Matola city, Beira in central Mozambique and Nacala in the north,
said the release.
</P>
<P>
Taking transport into account, prices in other regions could
be increased accordingly, it added.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique is not an oil-producing country. Its liquid fuel
prices are adjusted with the imported oil prices and the U.S.
Dollar exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
The latest fuel price change is in January. Since then,
prices for imported oil had been down by about eight to 20
percent, while the Dollar had been appreciated by about 0.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The retail fuel prices in Mozambique is quite high, which has
caused some people to drive to the neighboring country for
refilling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
