<HEADLINE> Iraq Reaffirms Endeavor to Implement Deal With UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf reaffirmed that Iraq will endeavor to implement
the accord signed with U.N. Chief Kofi Annan so that the
international embargo may be lifted as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement carried by the Iraqi News Agency Friday,
al-Sahhaf said that the efficient and objective implementation of
the accord, signed here on February 23 on peacefully ending
Iraq-U.N. crisis over arms inspection, would create an effective
atmosphere to accelerate the lifting of the embargo against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, he asserted the necessity of a balanced approach by
the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on dismantling Iraq's weapons
of mass destruction to avoid any biased practices.
</P>
<P>
A balanced approach would also afford the U.N. Security Council
and the international community the opportunity to discover that
whatever Iraq has said is the right thing, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that UNSCOM would accelerate the steps to
enable the Security Council to debate the lifting of the
U.N. sanctions as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed in 1990 after Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait. They can only be lifted after the UNSCOM verifies that
Iraq has destroyed all the banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.N. arms inspection teams, including a large group
led by Scott Ritter, a controversial U.S. arms inspector, made
surprise visits to 12 suspected sites Friday, including three
sites not under their regular monitoring, said a spokesman for
Iraqi National Monitoring Department.
</P>
<P>
The arms inspectors received full cooperation from the Iraqi
side and no problem was reported.
</P>
<P>
Ritter, called by Iraq as a "trouble maker," returned to
Baghdad on Thursday with some 50 inspectors.
</P>
<P>
He was prevented from carrying out arms inspection in
mid-January on grounds that the composition of his 16-member team,
including nine Americans and five Britons, was imbalanced.
</P>
<P>
Ritter told reporters that the sites he inspected Friday did
not include the presidential sites, which will be carried out
under special arrangements by Annan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
