<HEADLINE> Most Nigerian Households Engaged in Farming: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Federal Office of
Statistics (FOS) said Friday that an average of 61 percent of
households in the country are engaged in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
In a publication entitled "Major Social Indicators by Local
Government Areas in Nigeria 1993/94", FOS said Kebbi and Sokoto
states in northwest have 93 and 92 percent of such households,
the highest in the country.
</P>
<P>
Lagos state, the economic center where the former national
capital is situated, has the lowest figure of only two percent,
it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the publication, 31 percent of households in the
country source their water supply from streams, ponds or other
unsatisfactory places.
</P>
<P>
It also revealed that at the national level, 87 percent or
nine-tenths of Nigerians disposed of their refuse in
unsatisfactory places such as within their compounds or other
unauthorized areas, with Lagos having the lowest figure of 34
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
