<HEADLINE> S. African Security Guards End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A two-week strike by
security guards finally came to an end on Friday evening when the
unions and employers signed an agreement in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
The South African National Security Employers' Association
(SANSEA) and unions in the sector agreed on a 14 percent wage and
benefits package -- 10 percent in wage increases, three percent
in provident fund contributions and one percent as an annual
bonus.
</P>
<P>
The settlement was a victory for both parties and it was
unfortunate that there were injuries to non-striking workers and
damage to property, SANSEA chief negotiator Don Masterson said.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement which has been reached is a compromise
settlement but it does take us a step closer to the type of
conditions we would like to see in the industry," unions'
representative Randall Howard said.
</P>
<P>
He said the strike helped workers achieve an important social
benefit, a provident fund.
</P>
<P>
About 30,000 security workers began a nationwide strike on
February 23, demanding a 12 percent across-the-board salary
increase, a six percent company provident fund contribution, a
100 percent annual bonus, and double pay on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
The unions by Friday afternoon reduced their demand to 14
percent, including salary and provident fund.
</P>
<P>
The employers offered a package of 13.5 percent -- 10 percent
on wages, three percent on provident fund contributions and half
a percent as the annual bonus.
</P>
<P>
The parties negotiated amid applications to the Labor Court by
employers for the strike to be declared illegal and unprotected.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Appeal Court in Johannesburg on Thursday upheld last
week's Labor Court judgement that the strike by security guards
was legal and protected. The appeal by SANSEA against the
judgement was dismissed with costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
