<HEADLINE> Head of U.N. Special Group to Go to Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Jayantha Dhanapala, head of
U.N. Special Group for inspections of Presidential Sites in Iraq,
will travel to Baghdad Monday to prepare for the Group's
inspection activities there, it was announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The detailed inspection procedures have been finalized and
they will be presented to the U.N. Security Council Monday,
spokesman for U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Group was set up under the agreement reached between Annan
and Iraq on February 23 during Annan's trip to Baghdad to solve
the crisis over U.N. arms inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said an inspection team led by
American Scott Ritter resumed inspections in Iraq Friday. They
viewed three sites which were all declared sensitive by Iraq, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, there was full cooperation on the Iraqi side and
inspectors were able to inspect all of the sites to their full
satisfaction," Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
Ritter, previously branded a U.S. spy by Iraq, returned to
Baghdad Thursday and is expected to stay into the middle of next
week. His team is on the continuation of the work interrupted in
January.
</P>
<P>
Denying a press report that Executive Chairman of U.N. Special
Commission on arms inspections in Iraq (UNSCOM) Richard Buttler
did not inform Annan of Ritter's dispatch, Eckhard said Annan was
well aware of the matter.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said Annan will meet Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahaf on the subject of oil for food program here Monday.
</P>
