<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Concerned About Tensions in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz expressed grave concern on Friday over the clashes between
Serbian police and ethnic Albanians in Kosovo province, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
A written statement released by the Prime Minister's Office
said that Yilmaz held a telephone talk with President of Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia Slobodan Milosevic on the tensions.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz told Milosevic that Turkey is closely monitoring
developments in Kosovo, adding that Ankara is worried that the
escalating tension might disturb all the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Turkey is in favor of a solution to the
clashes which could maintain the territorial integrity of the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem will go to Belgrade this
weekend to deliver Milosevic a message from Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel concerning the Kosovo situation, Yilmaz said.
</P>
<P>
Tensions in Kosovo escalated on March 1 after an armed conflict
which led to the deaths of four policemen and 16 Albanians. Ethnic
Albanians, who account for 90 percent of the population in Kosovo,
have been seeking independence from Yugoslavia since 1981.
</P>
<P>
Fearing the Kosovo unrest could further disstablize the Balkan
region, some countries, including the United States, the European
Union countries and Russia, have urged the Milosevic government to
deal with it in a cautious and proper way.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which has close ties with Albania and ethnic Albanians
in the Balkans, has called on both parties involved in the
conflicts to solve their disputes through dialog. 
</P>
</TEXT>
