<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Entrepreneurs Welcome Institutional Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Managers of China's state-owned
enterprises, who have long suffered from government bureaucracy,
seem to be the most enthusiastic supporters of an institutional
restructuring plan proposed by the State Council, China's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which was submitted on Friday to the ongoing First
Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), China's top
lawmaking body, for examination, has become one of the most
popular topics in group discussions of the legislators.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers representing the country's business community agreed
that the existing structure of government institutions is an
outcome of central planning, and has hampered the development of a
socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
"I firmly support this reform plan, which I think is quite
appropriate," said Liu Hanzhang, a deputy from north China's Hebei
Province.
</P>
<P>
Liu, who is president of the Handan Steel Corporation, a
successful state enterprise that has been made a model of reform,
said that since a lot of government departments with redundant
functions have the right to directly interfere with enterprise
management, the enterprises have been prevented from seeking
development according to market demand.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, great powers possessed by these departments
also gave rise to the practice of trading power for money,
breeding corruption.
</P>
<P>
"The most serious problem of the current government structure
is its restraints on economic reforms," he said. "It's inevitable
to step up political restructuring when economic restructuring has
developed to a certain stage."
</P>
<P>
According to the State Council reform plan, China will cut its
central government departments from 40 to 29, and abolish 15
departments directly managing specific industrial sectors, such as
ministries of machine-building industry and coal industry.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that this round of institutional restructuring will
start in local governments as soon as possible, and set free a
large number of state-owned enterprises," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
Shi Jun, a deputy from east China's Shandong Province, said
that under a market economic system, enterprises have an
increasingly larger host of investors, a big difference from the
period of a planning economy, when the bulk of investment for
enterprises came from the government.
</P>
<P>
"Under such circumstances, it's no longer appropriate for the
government to retain the power of examining and approving every
new move in enterprise management," he said.
</P>
<P>
Excessive intervention in microeconomic development will also
diminish the macro-control capabilities of government departments,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Cai Dongcheng, another deputy from Hebei who is the boss of a
pharmaceutical corporation, said that the most direct beneficiary
of institutional restructuring would be the enterprise.
</P>
<P>
He called for early legislation on institutional restructuring
to ensure a successful government reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
