<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress Made in Cross-Strait Shipping, Says Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- There has been a breakthrough in
the issue on direct shipping across the Taiwan Strait as normal
channels have been established, but there remains a gap from the
direct links of trade, air, shipping and mail service.
</P>
<P>
Huang Zhendong, minister of communications, gave these remarks
today at a panel discussion of Taiwan deputies at the First
Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), which
opened Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He told the Taiwan deputies that four seminars have been
sponsored between the Chinese mainland and Taiwan on direct
shipping service, which resulted in the agreement of the mainland
and Taiwan businessmen in some issues. Non-governmental
organizations across the straits have been set up to promote such
services, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ships are seen sailing to and from major ports in the mainland
and Taiwan, Huang said. More than 1,100 voyages by 10 mainland and
Taiwan companies had been made across the Taiwan Straits,
transporting a total of 145,000 TEUs by the end of January this
year.
</P>
<P>
Apart from one mainland shipping firm, Huang said all the other
shipping companies have made profits from the cross-strait direct
shipping.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that such shipping links are only in the
initial stage because of the "no customs connection and no entry"
policy of the Taiwan authorities. However, he added, "It is a
breakthrough compared with no connection in the more than 40
decades."
</P>
<P>
Huang went on to note that improvements have been made in
shipping environment and conditions as Taiwan has put into use the
light buoy and lighthouse installations, which has provided safety
guarantees for cross-strait shipping.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan authorities, which used to impose strict limits upon
mainland-funded shipping companies, have allowed that solely
mainland funded shipping companies to dock at Taiwan seaports,
the minister said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
