<HEADLINE> Gulf FMs to Discuss Iraq, Iran Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) started a meeting of foreign ministers Saturday in Saudi
capital Riyadh to discuss the situations in Iraq, ties with Iran
and the Middle East peace process, the Kuwaiti News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, Kuwaiti Foreign Minister
Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah described a recent agreement signed
by the United Nations and Iraq as a crucial step to accomplish
arms inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan reached the agreement with
Iraq on February 23, under which Iraq will grant free access to
presidential sites to a special inspection team comprising
U.N. arms inspectors in Iraq and senior diplomats appointed by
Annan.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's refusal to allow the U.N. arms inspectors search for
weapons of mass destruction in presidential sites has prompted the
United States and Britain to unleash military threat to force its
compliance with the U.N. Special Commission charged with
eliminating the weapons.
</P>
<P>
Sabah urged Iraq to comply with the agreement, and expressed
the conviction that its implementation would be guaranteed, the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq must adhere to the implementation of all U.N. Security
Council resolutions concerning the liberation of Kuwait ...," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990 but was driven out during 1991 Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
The Riyadh-based Gulf Cooperation Council, a political,
economic and defense alliance, consists of six Arab countries of
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar,
Bahrain and Oman.
</P>
<P>
On Iran, the ministers will manifest optimism on prospects of
improving ties with Tehran in the light of an ice-breaking visit
to the council members by Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi
last year, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Ties between the Gulf Arab states and Iran, which were strained
following Iran's 1979 Islamic Revolution, started warming up after
moderate Iranian President Mohammad Khatami assumed power last
August.
</P>
<P>
Khatami has said that improving relations with Gulf Arab
countries is one of Iran's top priorities. This has been welcomed
by the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
But the ministers are expected to reaffirm the council's
steadfast position on three disputed Islands of Abu Mussa, Greater
and Lesser Tunbs in the Gulf, which are currently controlled by
Iran, but also claimed by the UAE.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Arabs support UAE's proposal to settle the issue
through arbitration by the International Court of Justice of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will also discuss the Middle East peace process,
according to the news agency.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Arab countries insist that Israel must stop hampering
the process and abide by the land-for-peace principle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
