<HEADLINE> Latvia Defends Handling of Russian-Speakers' Rally in Riga </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Latvia defended Saturday the
dispersing of a rally of Russian-speaking protesters in front of
City Duma in Riga by Latvian police on March 3 as "a legal and
self-defense act."
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Ziedonis Cevers told an extraordinary meeting
of the cabinet that the police acted "within the bounds of the
law," the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The police used batons only for the purpose of self-defense,
Cevers said, adding that they "have the legitimate right to use
this special means for self-defense in such situations."
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Latvian police pushed and dispersed a group of
mostly elderly Russian-speakers protesting against the high cost
of living.
</P>
<P>
Latvian Prime Minister Guntars Krasts has said the incident
might have been instigated by some forces interested in breaking
down Latvian-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
Krasts also alleged that Moscow might be involved in the
protest by a group of elderly Russian-speakers in the Latvian
capital of Riga.
</P>
<P>
The allegation caused strong repercussions from Moscow. On
Friday, Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin sternly
denounced the allegation.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Russian presidential spokesman Sergei
Yastrzhembsky warned that Moscow could limit trade with Latvia
over the recent violation of the rights of Russian-speakers in the
Baltic country.
</P>
<P>
A team responsible for Russia's foreign policy has recommended
that President Boris Yeltsin take steps to limit economic
relations with Latvia, the spokesman was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Latvia, whose economy relies considerably on Russian energy
supplies and resale of Russian exports, should be "more loyal with
regard to Russia's interests," Yastrzhembsky said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
