<HEADLINE> France's Burtin Wins First Down Hill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Nicolas Burtin of France won his
first ever World Cup downhill on Saturday and Hermann Maier became
the first Austrian man since 1970 to take the overall title in a
men's World Cup race in Kvitfjell of Norway.
</P>
<P>
Burtin, cameout strongly from three knee injuries between
December 1994 and January '97, flashed down Kvitfjell's Olympic
course in a winning time of one minute, 44.07 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Andreas Schifferer of Austria, the World Cup downhill champion
this season, skied out on the upper part of the 3,035-meter course
designed by former Swiss downhill great Bernhard Russi. That
mishap enabled compatriot Hermann Maier to clinch his first
overall title while sitting at home in Austria.
</P>
<P>
The last Austrian man's overall champion was Karl Schranz, who
won his second in 1970.
</P>
<P>
Maier, a two-time Olympic champion in Nagano last month didn't
compete in Kvitfjell because of a back injury. He was injured
during a World Cup race in South Korea after the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
With only five races left and a maximum of 500 points at stake,
Maier leads Schifferer 1,625 points to 1,034. 
</P>
