<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conditions Not Mature To Make RMB Fully Convertible: Bank Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- There will be no change in China's
resolve to make its currency fully convertible, but the country
will take a more prudent, cautious approach in handling the
progress, according to Chinese central bank governor.
</P>
<P>
"The direction will remain unchanged. But the financial crisis
in Southeast Asia reminds us of handling the process with
meticulous care and in a down-to-the-earth-manner," said governor
Dai Xianglong at a press conference organized by the on-going NPC
session here today.
</P>
<P>
China made the decision in 1993 to gradually realize the full
convertibility of RMB yuan, though without setting a timetable, he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
The country has already made yuan convertible under the current
account. However, said Dai, "conditions are not yet ripe to realize
full convertibility under capital account."
</P>
<P>
"A premature announcement of yuan's full convertibility will
be determental not only to the interests of the country, but to
that of the investors from overseas," the central bank governor
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
