<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Harnessing Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng today emphasized
the importance of taming the Yellow River, China's second longest,
in a group discussion attended by deputies from Henan Province to
the National People's Congress, in session here since last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The Yellow River has not caused any major flooding in the last
50 years but, fundamentally speaking, the danger of flooding has
not been uprooted," the premier said. "This calls for great
attention to the taming of the river."
</P>
<P>
Li Peng talked about the importance of the ongoing Xiaolangdi
Project near Luoyang, Henan, for the Yellow River's harnessing.
</P>
<P>
"The project will play a major role in flood prevention and
sand control," the premier said. "Efforts must be made to complete
the project and relocate affected people as scheduled."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the river's harm comes mainly from soil
erosion in the upper reaches of the river. "This calls for efforts
to conserve water and soil there," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged people along the Yellow River to pay attention to work
in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"Once soil erosion on the Loess Plateau is brought under
control, the amount of silt rushing down the Yellow River will go
down sharply," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng pointed out that the river is not rich in water
compared with the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
With water use on the rise along its length, the Yellow River
often dries up along its lower sections, Li said.
</P>
<P>
He called on provinces and regions along the river to make the
best use of the river's limited water and promote the development
of a water-efficient agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Province Sets Tourism Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 7 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province has
set tourism targets through the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The targets include hosting between 26.1 and 32.5 million
tourists by the year 2000, including 1.35 million overseas
tourists. Projected foreign exchange earnings from tourism are
expected to soar to over one billion US dollars annually, with
total tourism revenues accounting for between 6-7 percent of the
province's gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Fujian will host between 45 and 52.7 million tourists annually
by the year 2010, including 2.2 million overseas tourists. The
sector's annual foreign exchange earnings are expected to hit 2.5
billion US dollars, with tourism revenues accounting for some 9-10
percent of the provincial GDP.
</P>
<P>
Fujian, the native home of over eight million overseas Chinese,
has led the nation for nine consecutive years in terms of both
tourism revenues and total number of overseas tourists. Fujian
boasts abundant tourism resources, including nine national- and 19
provincial-level scenic zones covering 1,139 square
kilometers. Fujian also has some 200-odd sites under national or
provincial protection.
</P>
<P>
A total of 5.64 million overseas tourists visited Fujian between
1992-1997, with tourism accounting for 4.95 percent of the
province's GDP in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
