<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dealing With Water Pollution in Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, March 7 (Xinhua) -- China's Anhui Province has
treated polluted water in the Huaihe River basin and Chaohu Lake
area to stop the degradation of the local environment.
</P>
<P>
The provincial governments have spent 830 million yuan (about
100 million US dollars) on treatment projects and general water
quality is at Category-3 levels. All sources of industrial
pollution along the river now meet discharge standards.
</P>
<P>
A water treatment project on Chaohu Lake is using a
140-million-U.S. dollar loan from the Asian Development
Bank. Waste water discharged into the lake will be cut by 35.7
million tons, or more than half, when the project is completed.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, there will be 55 urban sewage treatment
plants built at a cost of 5-6 billion yuan in the Huaihe River
basin.
</P>
<P>
A series of local environmental regulations has been worked out
and law enforcement inspections have been made across the province
to ensure that the 757 polluting enterprises closed down in 1996
do not start up operations again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forum to Attract More Investment to Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- A two-day high level inter-
national conference on attracting trade and investment to Africa
is expected to open here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the organizing committee, "The Addis Forum",
which was sponsored by a group organizations and international
firms, those taking part in the conference include government
representatives and business executives from 16 African
countries, and heads of corporations and business concerns from
15 countries in north America, Europe, the Middle East and South
East Asia.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi and Ugandan President
Yoweri Museveni are among the keynoters during the conference
which organizers say "will be devoted to answering the theme
question of the conference: how to attract investment to Africa."
</P>
<P>
Africa attracts the lowest share of foreign direct investment
(FDI) in the world. According to the 1997 world investment report
published by the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development (UNCTAD), FDI rose by 10 percent in 1996 to a record
of 349 billion U.S. Dollars. However, of the 349 billion dollars
in FDI, developing countries received 129 billion U.S. Dollars,
and only 5.3 billion U.S. Dollars flowed to Africa and Africa's
share of FDI thus represent 1.5 percent of global FDI and 4.1
percent of developing world FDI. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
