<HEADLINE> Guangdong Province Encourages Private Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province, one of
China's economic powerhouses, has adopted new policies designed to
boost the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The new policies permit members of sector to open nursery
schools and hospitals, and to engage in sales of secondhand goods,
as well as pawnbroking and wholesaling books, according to local
government sources.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses which sign contracts to operate loss-making
state-owned enterprises will enjoy favorable policies.
Technology-intensive private firms will be granted the
same treatment as state-owned enterprises when applying for loans.
</P>
<P>
The 120,300 privately owned enterprises in the province at the
end of last year had total registered capital of 107.6 billion
yuan, and employed a work force of well over 1.5 million people.
</P>
<P>
The private sector has evolved into a major factor helping to
ease local employment pressures, with the sector providing jobs
for 84,000 members of the redundant work force in 1997 alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Members on Combating Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Members of China's top advisory
body expressed confidence in the government's ability to tackle
the unemployment problem and offered ways to combat unemployment
at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
A solution for layoffs is to boost economic development,
especially to develop the service industry that employs big
numbers of workers and expand medium and small-sized enterprises,
said Dong Fureng, a well-known economist, at the press conference
sponsored by the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC) National Committee, in session here since last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A key task at the present stage is to reform the social
security system, build an unemployment insurance system and
accelerate the development of a labor market, he said.
</P>
<P>
Laid-off workers engaging in self-employed commercial
businesses should be granted preferential treatment in taxation
and, in the meantime, laid-off workers should change their way of
thinking when looking for jobs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Huang Daneng, an executive vice-president of the China
Vocational Education Society, said his organization has opened
training courses for 150,000 workers and helped 30,000 laid-off
workers find new jobs in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Hu Deping, a member of the China Society for Promoting the
Glory Undertakings Program said entrepreneurs in non-public
sectors have invested 5.16 billion yuan in launching 2,300
projects and training 260,000 people in poverty-stricken areas in
the past four years. They will play an even bigger role in the
reemployment of laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
The Glory Undertakings Program is launched by private
businessmen in China to help the poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
