<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Palestinian Minister of Housing Abdul Rahman Hamad
announced that rehabilitating and renewing infrastructure in the
Palestinian National Authority self-rule areas need 3 billion
U.S. dollars, adding that the financial assistance given by donors
has not yet exceeded 2 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Abu Dhabi Emirate set up a water and
electricity authority as a step towards privatizing the power and
water sector in the emirate.
</P>
<P>
According to local press report, the authority, which started
operation on March 1, will be in charge of the water and
electricity affairs during the interim period.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Shareholders of the Arab Palestinian Investment Bank
approved setting aside a low-interest 35-million-dollar loan for
boosting the investment activities of the bank in the Palestinian
National Authority self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
This came at an ordinary session held by the General Assembly
of the Bank in Amman, the capital of Jordan, which also approved
the results achieved by the bank during the fiscal year 1997, but
nothing was revealed about the bank's budget.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The number of tourists who visited Yemen last year
stood at 80,000, and the revenues from tourism industry amounted
to 70 million dollars, according to Mohammed Mohammed Kafla, Vice
Chairman of Yemen's General Tourism Authority. Most of the
tourists were from Europe and Japan, he added.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon and Norway has signed a draft agreement to
avoid double taxation, local newspaper Daily Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Following the signing ceremony, Lebanese Minister of State for
Financial Affairs Fuad Sinyoura said that the agreement will
serve to encourage more investment in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
A similar accord with the United States is under discussion, he
added. 
</P>
