<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Charity Undertakings Make Headway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Charity undertakings in China such
as those assisting poor mothers and school dropouts have made much
headway, according to leaders of charity organizations speaking at
a press conference today sponsored by the ongoing First Session of
the Ninth National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC).
</P>
<P>
With an effort to help poor mothers, Project Happiness was
launched in 1994, according to Wang Guangmei, widow of late
Chinese president Liu Shaoqi and director of the charity's
organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 yuan (240 US dollars) is given to an impoverished
mother so that she can start a small business. When the life of
the mother has improved, the money has to be paid back. And the
money is then loaned to another mother.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the fund is used for education on medical care,
child bearing and farming.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, more than 30 million yuan had been raised
for Project Happiness, 68 projects had been carried out and nearly
30,000 poor mothers had become beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
Xu Yongguang, secretary-general of the China Youth Development
Foundation, said at the press conference that Project Hope has
assisted 1.847 million children to resume their education since
the foundation initiated the project nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,200 Hope primary schools have been set up across
the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Project Hope has played an active role in working together with
the government to boost elementary education in impoverished
areas, Xu Yongguang said.
</P>
<P>
The goal of Project Hope is to help 2.5-3 million children from
poor families and establish over 7,000 Hope primary schools
throughout the country, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coal Industry in Northwestern China Gets Re-employment Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, March 7 (Xinhua) -- A project in China's Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region has been designed to help poverty-stricken coal
miners who have been laid off the job establish businesses by
providing low-interest loans and unemployment relief.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia is one of China's six coal centers and has over 100,000
coal workers. In the '90's, about 15,000 workers were laid off to
improve efficiency. However, one of these people, Chen Fengqing,
made a lot of money in two years' time by establishing a chicken
farm in 1995, and then expanded her business to raising pigs and
running a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
She is just one example of laid-off people in the industry,
according to Song Tianyou, the vice-director of the coal
department. He attributed her success to the expanded
re-employment project. Coal enterprises in the region used various
ways to help the unemployed. By the end of 1997, about 8,600
people had found new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Song said that Ningxia's coal industry has 14 trades in
industrial, agricultural, and service work, with 488 factories,
430 products, and 20,000 employees. In 1997, the output value of
these was 700 million yuan, and profits, 60 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Developing labor-intensive industry is one way to solve the
problem, and unemployed people are being encouraged to open up
wasteland. Last year, farms in mining areas produced 4.3 million
kg of grain, 2.2 million kg of fruit, and 800,000 kg of meat,
fish, and eggs, all of which provided both salaries for workers
and more food for local tables. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
