<HEADLINE> Border Inspectors in Eastern China Getting Tough on Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Border inspectors in China's
Fujian Province have gotten some results in their crackdown on the
smuggling of drugs, firearms, and people in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Provincial border police found 261 cases of people smuggling
last year, involving 2,262 people, and arrested 263 ringleaders
and accomplices.
</P>
<P>
They also discovered 99 cases of smuggled goods, worth 55
million yuan (6.6 million US dollars), and seized 175 kg of heroin, 82
kg of "ice", and a number of smuggled firearms.
</P>
<P>
Priority has been given to controls on different types of
ships, which are an essential part of smuggling activities,
according to one frontier inspection force officer who said that,
in 1997, the force increased its size, held professional training
classes for its frontier guards, and set up a marine police
emergency system, all of which increased its effectiveness. 
</P>
