<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese City Encourages Major Overseas-Backed Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The city of Fuzhou, the capital of
China's Fujian Province, is classifying overseas-funded businesses
in three categories, depending on sales and exports, and gives
more support to major ones.
</P>
<P>
Group A refers to companies with annual sales of 12 million
U.S. dollars or more and exports of more than 10 million
dollars, or an investment of over 30 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Group B averages sales of 6 to 12 million dollars and exports
of 5 million dollars or an investment of 10 million to 30 million
dollars. Group C refers to all businesses below that.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yong, the city's deputy-mayor, told Xinhua that trial use
of the measure last year had successful results in key projects.
</P>
<P>
Fuzhou's economy depends a great deal on overseas capital,
according to Liu, who says that there are 94 A projects and 118 B
and they are the city's economic base and should get more
preferential treatment.
</P>
<P>
He said that more overseas-backed projects will be added to the
Groups A and B after some projects are opened to international
investment in May, which has been officially designated as
international investment month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
