<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebels May Intervene in Hostage Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) said Saturday that it will verify if its members are among
eight hostage-takers in the Davao Penal Colony (DAPECOL) in
Kapalong, Davao del Norte, the Southern Philippines, and may
intervene in the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Eight inmates of the Davao Prisons and Penal Farm Thursday
morning took five female prison employees hostage inside the
DAPECOL reception and diagnostic center, demanding the ouster of
the prison superintendent and construction of a mosque inside the
penal colony and talks with government officials.
</P>
<P>
Some people reportedly said that two or three hostage-takers
are MILF members and suggested that the MILF should intervene in
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the Philippine News Agency, Al Haj
Murad, MILF vice chairman, said Saturday that the rebel group will
verify if the hostage-takers are MILF members.
</P>
<P>
But he said that "whether they are MILF members or not, we are
open to suggestions what we can do to save the critical situation
involving victims from the weaker sex."
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader said that after Jesus Dureza, presidential
assistant to Mindanao, failed to end up the hostage crisis Friday,
people are seeking his intervention in the release of the five
female hostages.
</P>
<P>
The hostage-takers are armed with hand grenade, firearms and
bladed weapons, the Philippine News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the government already agreed to dismiss
the prison superintendent Jose Poblacion Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The rest of their demands were still being negotiated as of
press time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
