<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi FM Leaves for New York for Talks With Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf left here Saturday for New York to hold talks with
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, the Iraqi News Agency INA
reported.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi delegation headed by al-Sahhaf will discuss with Annan
the steps to be taken regarding the increase of oil Iraq is
allowed to sell under the U.N.-Iraq oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Under a new U.N. Security Council resolution which was passed
by the 15-member council on February 20, the amount of oil Iraq
can sell would increase from 2 billion U.S. dollars to 5.2 billion
dollars over six months.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq has said it is unable to pump more than 4 billion
dollars worth of oil in six months due to the decline of oil
prices in world market and lack of spare parts in its oil sectors.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi foreign minister will also continue negotiations
with Annan on the implementation of the Iraq-U.N. accords signed
on February 23 during the U.N. Chief's Baghdad trip.
</P>
<P>
Under the accords, Iraq had agreed to open its presidential
palaces to a special group composed of senior diplomats appointed
by Annan and experts drawn from the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating Iraq's banned weapons and the
International Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been unable to sell its oil on the open market since
the U.N. sanctions were imposed after Baghdad's 1990 invasion of
Kuwait. The oil-for-food deal, which began in December 1996,
allows Iraq to sell a restricted amount of oil to buy food and
medicine for its 22 million people suffering under the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions can not be lifted unless the U.N. weapons
inspectors verify that Iraq has been disarmed of biological,
chemical and nuclear weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
