<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Getting More Chinese Farmers To Industrialize Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 7 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of farmers in
China's Sichuan Province have begun to implement industrial
management of agriculture and increased per-capita income by 280
yuan annually in 1997, which is 40 percent more than unimproved
areas.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province spent 755 million yuan on 435 projects
of this type to develop nearly 640,000 ha of agricultural
production bases, with 46 billion yuan in output value.
</P>
<P>
Specialized farmers' associations at different levels have
promoted the process. The Farmers' Watermelon Association in
Leshan city, for example, has close contacts with 100,000
watermelon growers in 54 counties, and accounted for a 60-70
percent share of the province's watermelon market.
</P>
<P>
A joint stock cooperative system has also been introduced, and
more importantly, large enterprise groups have been encouraged to
join the campaign to industrialize local agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government to Protest Against Denktash's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government is to
lodge a protest against the content and the substance of a letter
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash sent to President Glafcos
Clerides on Friday, local press reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The government considers the letter as totally unacceptable
both in terms of substance and ethics. The President and his
Foreign Minister will take the necessary measures on both
counts," government spokesman Christos Stylianides was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the press reports, Rauf Denktash's letter was
communicated to Clerides by a senior U.N. official. But the letter
was sent back after Clerides refused to accept it because it was
written on "official" paper.
</P>
<P>
"The fact it was written on the paper of the pseudo-state and
signed by 'President' Denktash is unacceptable," Stylianides
said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Denktash and Clerides have communicated
by letters in the past but have avoided using titles.
</P>
<P>
In his three-page letter, Denktash essentially rejected any
notion toward a united federal Cyprus and reiterated his
long-standing demand for recognition of his breakaway republic,
which was unilaterally declared in 1983 in northern Cyprus and
recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Denktash demanded that efforts for a future settlement should
be based on the "acknowledgement of the existence of equal status
of our respective states."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
following a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and the international community, which recognized the
Republic of Cyprus, have been trying for decades to reunite the
divided island as a bizonal, bicommunal federal state, but so far
little tangible results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Denktash's position on the Cyprus issue has been hardened
following the European Union's (EU) decision to start accession
talks with the Cypriot government on March 31.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader has ordered suspension of bicommunal
contacts since last December in retaliation for the EU's move.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
