<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wooden Houses Giving Way to Brick in Rural China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Some old two-story wooden
structures in rural parts of an autonomous county of Qianjiang
Tujia and Miao minorities in Chongqing, in southwest China, are
giving way to brick houses.
</P>
<P>
Many farmers lived in thatched sheds that they shared with
livestock. Then later, as two-story wooden structures became more
affordable, the family would live upstairs and the animals
downstairs.
</P>
<P>
One farmer, Li Liangping, a Tujia who is in his late 40s, who
moved into a new brick house recently after years of living
together with his animals under the same roof, says, "Wooden
houses were much better than sheds, but the terrible smell from
downstairs was really hard to tolerate, especially in the hot
months."
</P>
<P>
But, some great changes have taken place in China's rural areas
since the reform and opening-up drive of the late 1970s, and now
75 percent of the villages in the county have roads or highways
leading out and 80 percent have electricity. Per-capita income of
farmers was 1,250 yuan and they produced 700 kg of grain.
</P>
<P>
Li's family earns more than 10,000 yuan annually from crops and
pigs, and outside the five-room house there's a neat pigpen. And,
70 percent of his neighbors have new brick houses.
</P>
<P>
"The disappearance of the wooden buildings means a new chapter
in efforts by local farmers to fight poverty, and it is better for
environmental protection because less wood is used," says Lei
Guofang, an official in charge of the county's poverty relief
work.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
