<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Has Not Postponed Legal Course Against U.S.  : Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has not postponed its
option of filing a suit against the United States on the issue of
F-16 planes, a spokesman for the Foreign Office said here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"We have decided in principle to file the suit, we are making
preparations for it," the spokesman told a weekly news conference.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether a law suit against the U.S. would in any way
hamper relations between Pakistan and the U.S., the spokesman
said: "I hope it will be seen as a reflection of our fair demand."
</P>
<P>
"We are well within our rights to demand supply of the planes
or return of our money," he added.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan entered into a contract with the U.S. in 1989 for
purchase of sixty F-16 aircraft and paid 658 million U.S. dollars
for the purchase.
</P>
<P>
However, neither the planes have been delivered nor the money
refunded to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan said on February 26
this year in the National Assembly that "we are in the process of
preparing ourselves for legal recourse in a U.S. court and have
engaged a law firm to study all aspects of the matter."
</P>
<P>
He also said that an amicable and early resolution of the F-16
issue with the U.S. is on top of the Pakistani government's
agenda.  
</P>
</TEXT>
