<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pingxiang, Trade Center along Sino-Vietnamese Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The small city of Pingxiang,
which was an important military area in China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, has become an important trade center along
the Sino-Vietnamese border.
</P>
<P>
The crowds of servicemen are gone, replaced by pedlars and
traders who jostle each other on the streets. The bullet-pocked
houses have been replaced by tall buildings and nearly 1,000
restaurants, beauty shops, and other stores that do business all
night long.
</P>
<P>
One restaurant owner says he's never troubled by theft or
robberies. Most business people are females, and some, known as
"open air bankers", carry bags of money and provide foreign
exchange services. Some restaurants have outdoor areas with
chafing dishes and beer in the early spring.
</P>
<P>
People have been coming here to do business since the early
1990s, as Sino-Vietnamese relations improved. In the last five
years, the city's exports and imports have had an average annual
increase of 20 percent, and in 1996, were valued at 1.23 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The city has 160,000 people, and a large "floating
population". The local Huayue Travel Agency has anywhere from
1-day to 9-day trips to Vietnam, with a three-day group visit to
Hanoi only priced at 250 yuan per person. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
