<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The South African Air Force
(SAAF) has announced that it is planning to buy 24 jet trainer
aircraft to replace its aging Impala fleet in early next century.
</P>
<P>
SAAF spokeswoman Lavern Machine said at the weekend that the
trainers would be funded by cutting back the number of fighter
aircraft the SAAF hoped to buy from 48 to 38.
</P>
<P>
"We have to stay with that budget," Machine said.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest Jane's Defense Weekly published in
Britain, the SAAF has planned to link its selection of a trainer
to that of the light fighter.
</P>
<P>
This would make both British Aerospace, which is presently
offering the Swedish Gripen fighter, and German Daimler-Benz
Aerospace, which is offering the AT2000 fighter, the leading
contenders to bid for the trainer contract. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
