<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Improving Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, March 7 (Xinhua) -- China's main agricultural areas are
making an effort to readjust agriculture at a time when buyer's
markets are growing in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Hubei Province is one example. From 1991 to 1995, farmers'
incomes had an annual average increase of 25.1 percent. But last
year, the figure dropped to 12.8 percent, even with the record
harvest. It had a good harvest for the third consecutive year in
1997, with a high level of production of major crops. But, most
crops ran into sales problems, and farmers' incomes were affected
as a result.
</P>
<P>
A striking contrast could be found in aquatic and meat
products, where there was rapid growth and good sales because
high-quality fish and lean pork got a large market share, industry
insiders say.
</P>
<P>
So, the provincial government decided to focus on market
adjustments, instead of the old increasing or reducing the size of
the crop-growing area. It plans to increase quality rice acreage
from the present 20 percent to 60 percent, and to encourage
diverse economies in rural areas and developing brand-name farm
produce and by-products.
</P>
<P>
The province will also place priority on industrializing
agriculture and on science and technology in agriculture and
increasing farmers' earnings. It is now working on getting local
universities and agricultural research institutes to work on
seeding projects and processing techniques.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
