<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Plans for Agricultural Modernization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government plans to
invest 343.9 billion shillings (about 300 million U.S. Dollars)
in the modernization of agriculture, media here reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of a one-day workshop on the Ugandan
plan for the modernization of agriculture Friday, Vice President
and Minister of Agriculture Specioza Wandira Kazibwe said that
the government has completed the search for an agricultural plan
which will enable the country to attain the goals of sustainable
economic development, poverty eradication and food security.
</P>
<P>
"The plan has now been elaborated into a strategy of
agricultural modernization with the main theme of improvement and
transformation", the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
Kazibwe disclosed that the plan includes commercialization of
agriculture to produce for marketing, improvement of agricultural
technology, introduction of disease and drought resistant seeds
and planting materials.
</P>
<P>
Others of the plan include targeting commercial agricultural
production in the districts, and involving the private sector in
agricultural production, processing and marketing, she said.
</P>
<P>
The vice president said to achieve the plan's targets, an
investment budget of 343.9 billion shilling has been drawn up for
five priority areas for a period of 1998 to 2002.  
</P>
</TEXT>
