<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Captures Northern Sierra Leone Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The West Africa peace-keeping force
known as ECOMOG has captured Kabala, a major town in north Sierra
Leone, forcing Johnny Paul Koromah, head of the toppled military
junta on a new run.
</P>
<P>
Reports in Lagos said Koromah fled from Kabala a few days
before Thursday, when the town fell to ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Koromah's troops fled in droves as ECOMOG approached Kabala,
the reports said, adding that ECOMOG is now in full control of
the town.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops has earlier seized Makeni, the northern regional
capital.
</P>
<P>
Residents of Kabala who had earlier fled from the town has
started emerging from bush, chanting and waving to ECOMOG troops,
said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted analysts as saying that the fall of Kabala
symbolized the end of resistance by troops loyal to Koromah,
whose military junta came to the end when ECOMOG forces entered
Freetown on February 12.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's civilian president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, who was
outsted by Koromah in the coup last May and has been in exile in
Guinea, is expected to return to Freetown to resume office next
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
