<HEADLINE> Li Ruihuan Gives Thumb Up For HK Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- China's central government has a
high opinion of the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administration Region in maintaining Hong Kong's stability and
economic prosperity since it was returned to China eight months
ago.
</P>
<P>
This was made known by Li Ruihuan, a member of the Politburo
Standing Committee of the Chinese Communist Party Central
Committee, when he took part in a group discussion attended by
people from Hong Kong and Macao as members of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference, in session here since last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the HKSAR government has exercised effective
administration in Hong Kong and that the Hong Kong people have
maintained their original lifestyle. The region has seen a vibrant
economy and social stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
These prove the correctiveness of the "one country, two
systems" policy and Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping's belief that
Chinese people in Hong Kong can govern Hong Kong well, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed satisfaction at the work of Tung Chee Hwa,
chief executive of HKSAR, and of people of different walks of life
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Li said the central government has always supported the work of
the HKSAR government. The most fundamental support, he said, is to
fully respect "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" and a high
degree of autonomy for Hong Kong as prescribed in the Basic Law of
the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The success of the "one country, two systems" policy in Hong
Kong and the continued prosperity of Hong Kong will be of great
significance for reform and opening up programs in the mainland,
for Macao's smooth return, and for a peaceful resolution of the
Taiwan question, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan noted Macao will return to the embrace of the
motherland in a little more than one year. Macao compatriots have
seen clearly the bright prospects of Macao in the implementation
of the "one country, two systems" policy in Hong Kong and are
expecting the day for its return to the motherland. "This is the
most favorable condition for a smooth transition in Macao," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
