<HEADLINE> Pak Prepares to Face Challenges in Globalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Saturday that his country has to prepare itself to
face new challenges in a globalized economy of today.
</P>
<P>
The South Asia, particularly Pakistan, is poised for rapid
growth in the wake of new emerging markets in the Central Asia,
said Sharif while addressing a meeting of heads of multi-national
companies in Pakistan's southern port city of Karachi.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's economy has been opened up for investment in many
sectors including agriculture, infrastructure and service sector
and the government has taken various measures to attract foreign
direct investment on repatriable basis, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
He urged multi-national companies to establish their production
facilities in Pakistan to tape potentials in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We are now ready to cater to all the needs of foreign
investors," Sharif said. He also said that the government is
considering to establish a permanent body to look into problems
faced by multi-national companies operating in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the Associated Press of Pakistan on
Saturday, the meeting was organized by the Board of Investment of
Pakistan for enhancing interaction between the government and
foreign investors to facilitate foreign direct investment in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The government has been urged by multi-national companies in
Pakistan to streamline tax collection and tariff structure,
improve law and order and fiscal imbalance, eliminate corruption
and ensure implementation of the existing policies to make the
country more attractive for direct foreign investment, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
