<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diversified Economy Facilitates Reemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- A rapid development of non-public
economic sectors is providing job opportunities for laid-off
workers discharged by bloated state-owned firms, according to
deputies to the Ninth National People's Congress, in session here
since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Qin Chaozhen, director of the Hebei Provincial Economic
and Trade Commission, said his province will dismantle 700,000
obsolete cotton spindles this year, which will result in 48,000
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
The laid-off workers, however, will be trained before getting
new jobs, Qin said.
</P>
<P>
The Hebei provincial government will spend 200 million yuan
this year financing reemployment programs, he said.
</P>
<P>
National spending for reemployment programs is expected to
total 10 billion yuan this year, according to government sources.
</P>
<P>
According to Qin, while some state enterprises are downsizing,
businesses of other ownership forms are now offering an increasing
number of jobs. Private clothing factories in Lixian and Rongcheng
counties in Hebei are recruiting more workers. Cashmere processing
alone employs 100,000 workers in the province's Qinghe county, he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy Yang Zhenbin, a vice-president of Anhui
Provincial Federation of Industry and Commerce, private businesses
have shown great interest in employing state-owned workers who are
regarded as being well-trained, experienced and disciplined.
</P>
<P>
A deputy from Wenzhou, in east China's Zhejiang Province, said
that one third of the 420,000 workers at state-owned enterprises
in the city have lost their jobs in downsizing programs, but so
far not a single one of the laid-off workers has ever visited the
municipal labor bureau for a job. Almost all of them have found
new jobs in collective and private businesses, become
self-employed or started businesses of their own, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highland Tibetans Have Enough Vegetables to Eat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Residents on the high plateau have
easy access to fresh vegetablest, Gyaincain Norbu, chairman of the
Tibet Autonomous Regional government, said today at a panel of the
ongoing First Session of the Ninth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Owning to harsh natural conditions and backward cultivation
techniques, local Tibetans had to eat merely radish, potato,
cabbage and a few other varieties of indigenous vegetable, and
supplies were even more dearth during the frigid winter-spring
season.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the introduction of greenhouse, plastic sheeting and
high-altitude cultivation methods, local vegetable production has
increased, and Tibetans are now able to eat fresh vegetables all
year round, Gyaincain Norbu said.
</P>
<P>
Around the capital city of Lhasa, ten large vegetable growing
centers with a combined area of 1,200 ha have been opened.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the autonomous regional government has encouraged
and assisted farmers and herdspeople to raise pig, cattle and
chicken so that the diet of local residents, either in urban
areas, or rural and pastoral regions have enriched and become
varied, the chairman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Breast Cancer Patients Surviving Longer: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. women with breast cancer
are surviving much longer now than in the past, said a study
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Average survival period after diagnosis, according to the
study, rose from 4.4 years in 1965 to 7.2 years in 1993 among
women whose breast cancer tumors had spread to nearby lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
For those not suffering from cancer spread, the study conducted
by the American Cancer Society said, the average survival period
rose from 8.5 years in 1963 to 11.7 years in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The finding was drawn from studies on the records of 25,000
breast cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
The study attributed the phenomenon to better and earlier
detection, increased use of chemotherapy and radiation along with
surgery, as well as better techniques for finding that cancer
cells had in fact spread.
</P>
<P>
U.S. women have an overall one-in-eight chance of developing
breast cancer in their lifetime, it said.
</P>
<P>
More than 180,000 U.S. women are diagnosed with breast cancer
annually, and 40,000 of them die of the disease, according to the
study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
