<HEADLINE> Gas Supply Disrupted in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Efforts are being made to bring back
normal gas supply to Bangladesh capital Dhaka after gas supply was
cut off in many parts for the third consecutive day Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of engineers and workers have been sent to repair the
damaged pipeline that disrupted gas supply on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The main pipeline of the Titas Gas Transmission and
Distribution Company Ltd., the sole gas supplier of the city, was
damaged when the pile driver hit the underground pipeline during
the construction work of a residential building of Bangladesh
Television near Rampura TV complex, reports said.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the city plunged into an unprecedented gas
crisis following the incident, and the authorities termed it as an
act of sabotage.
</P>
<P>
But Titas Gas officials said the accident occurred due to
alignment problem of the plot where the construction work was
going on.
</P>
<P>
Gas supply was partially resumed in different affected areas on
Thursday evening, but didn't last long, and low-pressure gas
supply was reported on Friday afternoon but was cut off in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying our best. It will take only five to six hours
after reaching the damaged point of the line at 22 feet under the
ground," Muqtadir Ali, managing director of Titas Gas was quoted
as saying Friday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
