<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Plant to Stop Raising Output for Environment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- China's third largest steel
producer, the Capital Steel Corp. in Beijing, which is also known
as "Shougang," has decided this year not to raise its output any
more, partly for soothing local residents' growing complaints
about air pollution.
</P>
<P>
"We'll shift our attention to the variety, quality and
marketability of our products, and intensify efforts to curb
pollution," said Bi Qun, president of Capital Steel, who is
attending the ongoing session of the Ninth National People's
Congress as a deputy.
</P>
<P>
Due to rapid economic growth and a population surge, the
Chinese capital has witnessed a fast decline in environmental
qualities in recent years. Local residents are most upset by the
city's worsening air pollution.
</P>
<P>
About 30 kilometers to the west of Tiananmen Square in downtown
Beijing, Capital Steel, which employs 210,000 workers, is regarded
as a leading air polluter for its huge daily discharge of
industrial dust and other harmful materials.
</P>
<P>
Though there is not yet a plan to move the behemoth out of
Beijing, Bi said, "We're ready to close a branch factory next to
the new railway station in the city."
</P>
<P>
Capital Steel, which had stressed output increases for decades,
last year produced eight million tons of steel, eight percent of
the country's total.
</P>
<P>
"We used to expect a yearly output of 10 million tons, but now
we have realized the conflicts between our ambitious goal and the
strategy of sustainable development China has adopted since the
early 1990s," Bi noted.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report to the current NPC session on
Thursday, Premier Li Peng reiterated that economic growth must not
be pursued at the expense of resources and the environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
