<HEADLINE> Nigeria Accuses Cameroun of Arms Build-up on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria Friday accused Cameroun of
deploying no fewer than 5,000 troops with heavy weapons on the
disputed Bakassi Peninsula, thus causing fresh tension in the
area.
</P>
<P>
A statement by the Defense Ministry in Lagos said, "Cameroun
is building massively in the Bakassi Peninsula. More than 5,000
troops with heavy weapons and vehicles have moved to the border
with Nigeria."
</P>
<P>
Nigeria repeated its condemnation of foreign assistance to
Cameroun on Bakassi, saying that six European nationals were
involved in the deployment.
</P>
<P>
"The massing of troops by the Camerounian government indicates
that they are preparing to attack and occupy some settlement in
the area," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria said it views the concentration of troops by Cameroun
at the border as an affront and appealed for restraint. It said
Nigeria is committed to amicable solution to the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The statement also accused Cameroun soldiers of attacking
Nigerian civilians in the last two weeks, resulting in the death
of an unspecified number of people.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Cameroun have been clashing since early 1994 on
Bakassi, a territory of about 1,000 square kilometers and
believed to be rich in fishery and oil resources.
</P>
<P>
The case was filed to the International Court of Justice by
Cameroun in 1994 and is currently being heard at Hague, the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, Nigerian lawyers at Hague have
accused Cameroun of nurturing an ambition to seize the disputed
area to enlarge its maritime frontier and gain a much larger zone
than it could obtain through negotiation.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers urged the court to decline adjudication and allow
bilateral and multilateral mechanism to resolve the dispute, the
reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
