<HEADLINE> Spindle-Cut Drive Exerts No Impact on Cotton Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Deputies to the First Session of
the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) shared the view that
the endeavor to reduce spindles will not effect cotton production
in northwestern Xinjiang, China's largest cotton producer.
</P>
<P>
The cotton output in Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, makes up
a quarter of China's total annual output. Two thirds of Xinjiang's
cotton output is transported to other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Wang Lequan, secretary of the autonomous regional Party
Committee, said "in the wake of a nationwide agricultural
restructuring, the domestic demand for cotton far exceeds the
supply, but added that "we should still tap production potential,
increase cotton output year by year and and raise the quality of
cotton varieties."
</P>
<P>
China expects to cut 10 million obsolete cotton spindles to
bring the number of spindles nationwide to 30 million in the next
three years, in a bid to invigorate its textile industry.
</P>
<P>
"If the country retains these obsolete spindles, it is
hard for the ailing textile industry to get out of red," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
China's textile industry is expected to operate on a fairly
large scale and embark on a road of sustained growth upon the
completion of the readjustment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China will back cotton production in the upper and
lower reaches of the Yangtze River and Xinjiang region and adopt a
series of preferential policies, including allocation of more
funds for cotton production and implementation of the export
refund system.
</P>
<P>
According to participants in today's panel discussion, cotton
production will still be a profitable industry in Xinjiang and,
with increased output, local cotton growers will have more income.
</P>
<P>
Relevant sources disclosed that China will invest 11.15 billion
yuan (1.34 million US dollars) in building cotton production bases
in its Ninth Five-Plan period (1996-2000). Some 3.25 billion yuan
(390 million US dollars) have so far been used. Under this scheme,
Xinjiang is going to produce 1.5 million tons of cotton by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a woman NPC deputy and cotton expert called for still
greater efforts to be made for application of agro-science and
control of cotton diseases and insect pests.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
