<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ground Solid for Stable Exchange Rates of RMB: Economist (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- A noted economist said that the
foundation is solid for the Chinese currency renminbi (RMB) to
have stable exchange rates against the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
On the foreign exchange market, supply and demand decides the
relative prices of different currencies, said Xiao Zhuoji, a
professor from Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, there have been adequate supplies of US dollars on
China's foreign exchange market, and demand for RMB has kept
increasing. The demand and supply of US dollars and RMB are
basically balanced, while demand for RMB is bigger than supply,
Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
"The situation has lasted successively for three years, and the
trend is expected to remain unchanged," the professor said.
</P>
<P>
China's balance of international payments is good, and the
country's foreign exchange reserves have increased, he said.
</P>
<P>
From 1994 to 1997, China experienced a surplus in both current
and capital accounts. Its foreign exchange reserves increased from
21.2 billion US dollars in 1994 to 139.9 billion US dollars at the
end of 1997, providing an important condition for RMB's stable
exchange rates against the US dollar, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The structure of China's foreign funds and foreign debts is
rational," Xiao said. At the end of 1997, China had used more than
320 billion US dollars of foreign funds, two-thirds of which had
been foreign direct investment with the rest being loans, or
China's debt.
</P>
<P>
Long and medium-term debts make up 88 percent of China's
existing foreign debts, and short-term debts account for only 12
percent; annual repayment rate is less than ten percent. Payment
servicing debts each year is about 10 billion US dollars, or seven
percent of the country's foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
"This also acts as an important condition for the RMB's
stability," the professor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ground Solid for Stable Exchange Rates of RMB: Economist (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Strict supervision over the financial market and gradual
opening-up of the country's financial business have helped
stabilize the exchange rates of RMB, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Xiao Zhuoji, the opening-up of China's foreign
exchange market was carried out in three steps. In early 1994, the
dual exchange rate system was replaced by a unified system. RMB
was made convertible under the current account in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
The third step is to make RMB fully convertible. Because
convertibility under the capital account is not ready yet, RMB
cannot be converted freely yet.
</P>
<P>
The process of step-by-step opening-up conforms to China's
present economic strength, its foreign exchange supervisory system
and its ability to adapt to the international market, he said.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, is also a reason why China is able to resist
raids from speculative foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
A booming economy and low inflation are also stabilizing
conditions for the Chinese currency, he said.
</P>
<P>
A stable RMB is conducive to a steady development of China's
own economy, to stabilizing economic relations between China and
other countries and regions, and to foreign investment, the
economist said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the RMB's stable exchange rate will enhance the
confidence of southeast Asian countries in extricating themselves
out of the financial crisis as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
