<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Cuts Civil Service by 24 Percent over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 7 (Xinhua) - Tanzanian government has
reduced its civil service from 355,000 to 271,000, a 24 percent
cut, over the past five years to make it more effective and
efficient, an official has said.
</P>
<P>
George Yambesi, director of the policy development in civil
service department, told an Eastern and Southern African
consultative meeting in northern city of Arusha Friday that the
civil service would be further cut to 225,000 in accordance with
a proposed new service employment policy.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the new policy would provide broad
guidelines on instituting a merit-based civil service to enhance
salaries for professionals and top civil servants to levels
comparable to those in the private sector and raise the minimum
basic salary to the minimum living standard.
</P>
<P>
"A new code of ethics and conduct and a performance
measurement oriented staff appraisal system will also be
instituted," he told senior servants from Kenya, Uganda, Zambia,
Zambabwe, South Africa, Mozambique and Malawi.
</P>
<P>
A survey in 1996 indicated the civil servants in Tanzania were
the lowest paid comparing with other countries in the region,
Yambesi said, partly because of a prevalent existence of ghost
workers on the payroll.  
</P>
</TEXT>
