<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Used to Upgrade China's State Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- A large number of unprofitable
state-owned enterprises in northeastern Liaoning Province have
been revitalized thanks to technological upgrading with use of
foreign funds in recent years.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, Liaoning has absorbed 3 billion U.S.
dollars to carry out technological transformation in 2,200
state-owned enterprises, 32 percent of which were large and
medium-sized ones, said Provincial Governor Zhang Guoguang today,
who is a deputy to the ongoing First Session of the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPV) in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The annual output value of the firms that have been retooled
with foreign funds climbed to 18 billion yuan, (2.17 billion US
dollars), or one third of the figure gained by Sino-foreign joint
ventures in Liaoning. Their export value came to 1.7 billion U.S.
dollars, making up 65.3 percent of the export of local joint
ventures and 24 percent of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
Introduction of investment from overseas has assisted local
state-owned industrial firms to pool their stocked assets
with a total value of 40 billion yuan (4.8 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Province boasts more than 1,000 large and medium-sized
state-owned enterprises, or one tenth of the national total.
However, nearly half of the these enterprises, built in the 1950s
or 1960s, are equipped with obsolete facilities, and their products
are not so competitive.
</P>
<P>
Using their workshops, sites and existing equipment as capital
stock, local state-owned enterprises were encouraged to form joint
ventures with overseas partners over recent years.
</P>
<P>
The Dalian-based Bingshan conglomerate, is a case in point. It
has formed 18 joint ventures with the United States, Japan, Italy
and Hong Kong, bringing its total assets to 4 billion yuan (482
million US dollars). Its sales value topped 2.5 billion yuan (300
US dollars), and exports reached 28 million US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
