<HEADLINE> Angolan Peace Process to Finish by Month-End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The new timetable for the Angolan
peace process mapped out Friday sets March 31st as a new deadline
for the final peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
The new timetable for peace was the result of the proposal by
UN Deputy Representative to Angola Behrooz Sadry, after three
days of discussion.
</P>
<P>
Antinio Dembo, vice chairman of the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), issued a communique Friday
to start the total disarmament of its military forces Friday as
outlined in the new proposal.
</P>
<P>
UNITA's communique promises to disband all the remaining armed
men in 15 spots throughout the country on March 11 and 15, and
all the officials at the Bailundo City, UNITA headquarters, would
be deprived of their military ranks by March 19.
</P>
<P>
The new proposal was out after UNITA undertook a series of
sabotage activities against the peace deal signed in Lusaka 1994,
and the February 28 deadline for final peace was broken in the
country. 
</P>
