<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Members on High-Tech Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- A high-tech industry can take
shape and develop to drive China's economic growth sustainably if
the government takes realistic measures to boost its development,
said members of China's top advisory body.
</P>
<P>
Gu Shengzu, a member of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee and a Wuhan
University professor, said development of a new and high-tech
industry is the key to enhancing China's comprehensive strength
since new and high technologies have great potential to boot
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Gu has put forward several proposals at the ongoing session of
the CPPCC National Committee, including one on the establishment
of a high-level co-ordinating mechanism and the mapping out of a
unified strategic plan to boost the development of a high-tech
industry.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the commercialization of high and new
technologies involves high input, high risks and big economic
returns. Owing to high input and high risks, he said, only 10-15
percent of patented technologies in China -- more than 20,000 a
year -- and provincial-level recognized research results -- 25,000
a year-- are put to commercial use.
</P>
<P>
The first proposal put forward during the ongoing CPPCC session
is about encouraging risk investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
The key to developing a high-tech industry is to have people
with genuine technological know-how, said Xiong Xingmei, a
professor from Tianjin-based Nankai University, who suggested that
preferential policies be adopted to encourage more Chinese
students studying overseas to return.
</P>
<P>
Liu Shu, a CPPCC national committee member and vice-chairman of
China Association for Science and Technology, proposed providing
popular education on science and technology, suggesting that more
science and natural museums be built across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
