<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Station Raided in Coastal Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Armed raiders attacked a police
station in Kenya's Coast Province Thursday night, slashed an
officer on duty and fled with a G-3 rifle and 20 rounds of
ammunition, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The attack, which took place in Mariakani Police Station
between 8:00 to 9:00 p.m., is the second attack on a police
station in the province in the last six months, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Five suspects have been arrested and taken to coastal capital
Mombasa for further interrogation following a swoop in the town
which netted an estimated 70 suspects.
</P>
<P>
"We can not rule out anything but I do not want to comment
until the investigations are completed," Coast police boss
Japheth Mwania said.
</P>
<P>
According to Constable Jacto Chibo, who now is admitted at the
hospital with leg and head wounds, the raiders whom he estimated
between eight and 10 in number, had posed as relatives who wanted
to see an inmate.
</P>
<P>
"I told them to wait outside the gate while I checked the
report office but they pounced on me with machetes and swords in
a bid to steal the rifle but I clung to it," he said.
</P>
<P>
They slashed his head and arms as they struggled to steal his
gun.
</P>
<P>
His colleagues at the reporting desk then opened fire on the
attackers who retreated into the town and disappeared before a
massive swoop was launched a few hours later.
</P>
<P>
Police sources confirmed that all outlying police stations had
been ordered to provide reinforcements to Mariakani area as fears
of another attack mounted.
</P>
<P>
Chibo said that the raiders told him that they "would be back
with reinforcements later."
</P>
<P>
According to Mariakani residents, police reinforcements
arrived from a nearby General Service Unit and went into the town
arresting anyone in the streets.
</P>
<P>
Scores of residents had by Friday camped outside the Mariakani
Police Station waiting to see their relatives who had been
divided into several groups and placed under heavy guard.
</P>
<P>
Mariakani town remained tense the whole day Friday and
businessmen complained of poor business as many people stayed at
home waiting for the situation to return to normal.
</P>
<P>
Last August, heavily armed raiders attacked Likoni Police
Station in Mombasa District, and killed 13 people, among them six
policemen. The raid was the start of an orgy of violence which
left over 70 people dead within a month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
