<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stablizing Currency Not a Political Consideration: Bank Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- China's central bank governor
said that maintaining a stable RMB value is not the personal will
of Chinese leaders, but a reflection of both supply and demand on
the exchange market and overall performance of the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
Over the past four years, the Chinese yuan has actually
appreciated and the country's foreign currency reserve has grown
by 120 billion U.S. dollars to 140.3 billion US dollars by the end
of February, Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of
China, said at a press conference hosted by the on-going NPC
session earlier today.
</P>
<P>
Referring to financial turmoil in Southeast Asia, Dai said#,
China's export and investment from overseas this year will be
likely affected, but several factors are working to help balance
international payment.
</P>
<P>
The labor cost in China is generally much cheaper than in
Southeast Asian countries, and there is no sign that toy and
textile export as the country's predominant export items will be
shrinking.
</P>
<P>
"It is entirely possible that China will have a trade
balance, even a moderate surplus," said the central bank
governor, who further predicted that the foreign capital inflow
this year would be around 30 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China's foreign debt is not big in size and 80
percent of which is long-term debt, therefore there is no need to
convert the Chinese currency to pay foreign debts, explained Dai.
</P>
<P>
"China's foreign exchange reserve will continue to grow this
year, though not in a pace as fast as last year," said Dai. "So
the pressure for RMB to further appreciate is declining, but it is
certain that yuan will not depreciate."
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis in Southeast Asian is currently showing
signs of subsiding, said the Chinese top banker."I believe that in
one or two years the economy in Southeast Asia will recover and
reembark on the road of development." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yellow River Delta to be Attractive Investment Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The Yellow River Delta in Shandong
Province, east China, is expected to become another new investment
zone in the country, according to a deputy to the National
People's Congress, in session here since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Shi Jun, mayor of Dongying City, Shandong Province, said
Shandong is making plans to boost the development of the delta
area and the central government is very interested in the project.
</P>
<P>
Shi said, of the country's three famous delta areas created
respectively by the Pearl River, the Yangtze and the Yellow River,
only the Yellow River Delta area remains to be exploited on a
massive scale. The other two have achieved rapid economic growth
over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
Shi said the Yellow River Delta area has China's second largest
oil field, the Shengli, and half of the area is still waste land,
which can be turned into fertile fields.
</P>
<P>
According to Shi, the delta's development has a strong appeal
for international organizations; the central and provincial
governments have put the delta's development on their agendas as a
priority item; and the United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
has decided to support the delta's development as its priority
project in China in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that the delta has become one of the
country's key bases for agricultural development. Dongying City in
the delta has been approved by the central government to be a
coastal economic development zone, enjoying preferential policies
from the state. Shandong Province has massive plans to build the
area into major production bases for energy, chemicals, farm
products and aquatic products, according to Shi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor of Shenzhen on Necessity of Planned Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The eight percent economic growth
rate for China's national economy in 1998 as proposed by the
government is "necessary" and "possible," according to Li Zibin,
mayor of Shenzhen, China's first special economic zone.
</P>
<P>
In China with a big population, ten million people enter the
labor market each year. With slower growth, employment will become
difficult and the society will not be stable, said the mayor who is
in Beijing attending the National People's Congress as a deputy to
the country's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
Without a certain speed of growth, revenues and expenditures
will be hard to balance, nor can increasing material and cultural
needs of the people be met, he said.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth is driven by three factors, namely investment
in fixed assets, consumer demand and exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past ten years, investment in fixed assets
has constituted half of the driving force behind China's high
economic growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This year planned investment in fixed assets will increase by
10 percent over last year, providing a guarantee for a right
economic growth rate," Li Zibin said.
</P>
<P>
He maintained that investment should be channeled mainly into
five areas: farming-related projects, infrastructure and energy,
high-tech industries, residential housing and technical upgrading
of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In cities and towns, reform aimed at commercializing
residential housing is expected to make real estate development a
new growth area, he said.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises should study the rural market with a view to
providing more marketable goods to farmers. In the meantime,
farmers should be assisted to raise their income and have less
burden so that the rural market can be activated.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest difficulty lies in export, and solutions in this
regard must be worked out," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since Shezhen was made a special economic zone in 1980, it has
had stunning growth economically, with its GDP having increased
from 196 million yuan in 1979 to 113 billion yuan (13.6 billion US
dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The city has set its economic growth rate at 14 percent for
this year, the highest among 35 major cities of the country.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the special economic zone exported 25.5 billion US
dollars worth of goods, 14 percent of the national total, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We can feel the heavy responsibility," the mayor said. "We
will do our utmost to contribute to fulfilling the national
eight-percent growth goal."
</P>
<P>
The eight-percent economic growth rate for China's national
economy in 1998 was proposed by Premier Li Peng in his government
work report he delivered last Thursday at the opening session of
the National People's Congress.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 07:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Faces Huge Budget Deficit, Says Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait may face the second
largest budget deficit since Gulf war in 1998-99 fiscal year if no
action was taken to rectify the steep decline of oil prices, a
report by a governmental economic consultant agency said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shall Economic Consultants said in its weekly economic
report released Friday said that the budget deficit for the fiscal
year 1998-99 (July 1 to June 30) is expected to exceed the 2
billion Kuwait Dinars (6.6 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This will be the highest after the 5.349 billion dinars (17.65
billion U.S. dollars) deficit registered in 1990-91 fiscal year
when Kuwait has to pay the cost of liberation from Iraqi
occupation.
</P>
<P>
The report said that initial information indicate that public
expenditures may reach 5.19 billion dinars (17.12 billion
U.S. dollars) against 3.127 billion dinars (10.3 million
U.S. dollars) in revenues, leaving a deficit of 2.063 billion
dinars (6.8 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Unofficial figures showed Friday that in fiscal year ending
June 1997, Kuwait posted a budget surplus of 502 million dinars
(about 1657 million U.S. dollars) for the first time in 15 years,
mainly as a result of higher oil prices.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the Kuwaiti revenues are from oil
exports.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait was granted a new production quota of 2.19 million
barrels per day from 2.0 million barrels per day during the first
half of 1998 under a new OPEC output ceiling agreed last year.
</P>
<P>
But an anticipated increase in revenue was not resulted
because of a steady fall in oil prices over the past four months
to their lowest in four years and it is expected Kuwait GDP would
slow down this year resulted from over production of some OPEC
member countries and bad economic situation in Asia which imports
about half of Kuwait's oil exports.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shall expressed pessimism about the possibility of reaching
an agreement among OPEC members in the near future to stop the
decline in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
It did not expect OPEC to hold an emergency meeting in the
near future, suggesting that the current situation should be
allowed to continue for another two months or until the oil
prices drop below 10 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's current oil exports sales in the world market is at
10 to 11 U.S. dollars a barrel comparing with a 16 U.S. dollars
high last year when the world oil market saw an average prices of
21 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait government bodies were recently asked to reduce their
expenditures by 25 percent in the remaining period of the fiscal
year 1997-98 due to the drop of oil revenues.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Oil Minister Issa Al-Mazidi Friday called on fellow
OPEC member Venezuela and other OPEC over-produces to cooperate
with the rest of the cartel to help turn round the slump of world
oil markets.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the prices would rally and settle at a just and fair
level for both producers and consumers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
