<HEADLINE> Kournikova Survives First Round at Evert Cup Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Anna Kournikova of Russia came
back from the brink of defeat in the first round of the Evert Cup
to beat the 77th-ranked Alexia Dechaume-Balleret of France 3-6,
6-4 and 6-0 in Indian Wells on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchwoman led the 24th-ranked Kournikova 6-3, 4-1 when
the 16-year-old Russian took control, winning the next 11 games to
seize the match.
</P>
<P>
But another teen, 46th-ranked Mirjana Lucic who at 15 years old
as the youngest player in the Evert Cup draw, did not have a
successful first-round outing. Lucic lost to tour veteran Naoka
Sawamatsu of Japan 6-2, 4-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Three other seeds were winners on the opening day --
11th-seeded Ai Sugiyama of Japan, 13th-seeded Ruxandra Dragomir of
Romania and 15th-seeded Natasha Zvereva of Belarus.
</P>
<P>
The 17th-ranked Sugiyama defeated 24th-ranked Kerry-Anne Guse
of Australia 6-3, 6-3. The 21st-ranked Dragomir defeated Cara
Black, sister of ATP Tour players Byron and Wayne Black, 6-3,
6-3. The 23rd-ranked Zvereva posted a 6-2, 6-4 win over
82nd-ranked Sonya Jeyaseelan of Canada.
</P>
<P>
Martina Hingis of Switzerland, Lindsay Davenport of the United
States and Steffi Graf of Germany -- who were all to swing into
action Saturday -- head the list of the 16 seeded players at the
Evert Cup. The top eight seeds received first-round byes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
