<HEADLINE> Israeli PM in Norway for Mideast Deadlock Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu was in Oslo today in the hope that Norway, who brokered
the landmark Middle East peace accords in 1993, can help put the
stalled peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
Norwegian Prime Minister Kjell Magne Bondevik, who met the
Israeli premier, said Norway was prepared to help revitalize peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that we are here indicates that we have not given up
on Oslo," Netanyahu said after arriving at Oslo's international
airport.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said he will discuss with the Norwegians the opening
of the Palestinian airport and an industrial park in Gaza, the
settlements and the reinitiation of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The now deadlocked Oslo accords were signed after a string of
secret talks hosted in Norway in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The accords, which entailed mutual recognition between Israel
and the Palestinian Liberation Organization, established a
detailed timetable for Israel's disengagement from occupied
territories and stipulated that a permanent settlement of the
Palestinian question be in place by December 1998.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu will meet Foreign Minister Knut Vollebaek on
Saturday. Earlier, Vollebaek told Norwegian NRK radio he did not
expect any breakthrough in the peace process during Netanyahu's
visit.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who has made stops in Spain and Germany, will travel
to London on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
