<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Managing Well Large Enterprises While Adopting a Flexible
Policy Toward Small Ones"
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Following is an explanation for
the term "Managing Well Large Enterprises While Adopting a
Flexible Policy Toward Small Ones" mentioned in Chinese Premier Li
Peng's government work report to the Ninth National People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
"Managing Well Large Enterprises While Adopting a Flexible
Policy Toward Small Ones" are two important measures adopted by
the Chinese government to put forward the reform of state-owned
enterprises in China.
</P>
<P>
It means that the state will concentrate on managing well large
state-owned enterprises or enterprise groups and loosen control of
smaller ones in a bid to improve their vitality.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Chinese Government announced that large
state-owned enterprises were the backbone of the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
The state has given priority to boosting development of
1,000 large state-owned enterprises while relaxing control of
240,000 smaller ones with an aim to let them to survive in market
competition.
</P>
<P>
The state encourages small enterprises to experiment with all
forms of management and organization that reflect the law of
social production and invigorate enterprises. The joint stock
system and joint stock partnerships have been introduced on a
trial basis in various parts of the country to invigorate the
national economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Association Between Strong Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is a kind of merger in nature. But the two or more parties
involved don't work for the aim of annihilation. Large scale
industrial and commercial enterprises, which have connections in
production, carry out effective annexation in a bid to take each
other's strength, increase product varieties and accumulate more
assets.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government encourages the association between
strong enterprises, describing this form of assets reorganization
an effective way to the development of state-owned enterprises.
It is conducive to capital operation, development on a large
scale and improvement of state-owned enterprises'
competitiveness on world market and rational readjustment of
economic structure.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin stated, in his report at the 15th
national congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC), "By using
capital as the bonds and rely on the market forces, we shall
establish highly competitive large enterprise groups with
trans-regional, inter-trade, cross-ownership and trans-national
operations."
</P>
<P>
Association between strong enterprises is undoubtedly
beneficial to the formation of large enterprise groups.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chinese government stresses that the merger and
reorganization must keep to the market-oriented principle.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Figures for China's Economic &AMP; Social Development in 1997 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Of the 2,500 enterprises which have been selected for
participation in an experiment to establish a modern enterprise
system, 1,989 have become corporations; the number of cities
selected for carrying out a pilot project to optimize the capital
structure increased from 58 to 111; the number of businesses
selected for experimenting with the formation of enterprise groups
rose from 57 to 120; by the end of 1997, 675 state-owned
enterprises in selected experimental cities had gone through
bankruptcy procedures and 1,022 had been merged with other
enterprises, resulting in the laying off of 1.69 million redundant
workers; state-owned industrial enterprises scored an 11.9 percent
increase in profits after deducting losses; a system for ensuring
a minimum standard of living has been established in more than 330
cities;
</P>
<P>
-- Imports and exports totaled 325.1 billion US dollars, an
increase of 12.1 percent over the previous year, with a surplus of
40.3 billion US dollars; exports accounted for 182.7 billion US
dollars, rising by 20.9 percent; the export of machinery and
electronic products amounted to 59.3 billion US dollars, up 23
percent;
</P>
<P>
-- A total of 64 billion US dollars in foreign funds was used
during the year; direct foreign investment came to 45.3 billion US
dollars; foreign loans amounted to 12 billion US dollars; and
foreign investment brought in through shares issued abroad and
other routes amounted to 6.7 billion US dollars;
</P>
<P>
-- Radio coverage has been extended to 85.8 percent of the
population and television coverage, 87.4 percent;
</P>
