<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Stops Deforestation: Government Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica has eventually stopped
its deforestation process after years of efforts, a government
report published on Friday showed.
</P>
<P>
The report said the success should be contributed to the
nation's environmental policy adopted in 1997, which, instead of
promoting deforestation for agricultural development, sought to
control lumbering and create new ways to protect forests through
economic means.
</P>
<P>
Above all, the policy reversed the deep-rooted practice that
banks did not accept lands of forest as a security for loans.
</P>
<P>
A total of 50,000 hectares of forests in Costa Rica were cut
every year in the 19870s. But since then, lumbering started to
decrease and came to a halt in 1997 after 10 years of efforts in
environment protection.
</P>
<P>
Satellite maps show that forests now cover 40 percent of the
country, a figure well above the 10 percent average for other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica has also launched an international program, seeking
funds to preserve its forests. It has joined other wooded
countries to seek compensations from big atmosphere polluters
since forests are major absorbent of gases that cause the hothouse
effect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
