<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright started an official visit to Italy Friday for talks with
Italian leaders on bilateral relations and issues of Iraq, the
Balkans and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Upon her arrival at the Ciampino airport, Albright said
U.S. President Bill Clinton and his government hope to find out
the full truth about the February-3 cable car tragedy in northern
Italy as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Albright met with Italian President Oscar Scalfaro later in the
day, but details about their talks are not immediately known. She
will meet with other Italian leaders on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On February 3, a U.S. Marine aircraft -- EA-6B surveillance
plane -- sliced a cable car line near Cavalese, killing all 20
people on board.
</P>
<P>
The incident strained relations between Washington and Rome.
"But we are allies. We have responsibilities to each other.
That's why our troops have been here with Italy's permission for
so many years," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
She added that Washington will do everything to find out the
full truth and ensure nothing similar will happen again.
</P>
<P>
Just few hours after Albright landed here, Francesca Trombino,
attorney for U.S. colonel Richard Muegge, the commander of the
EA-6B plane, was hammered to death by an unidentified man near her
office.
</P>
<P>
But police are not sure whether Trombino's death is linked with
the cable car tragedy. 
