<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to lift Foreign Exchange Volatility Band </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will heed
the suggestion of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to allow
the peso to float more freely against the dollar at the spot
market by lifting the volatility band.
</P>
<P>
This was contained in a memorandum of economic and financial
policies forged between the Philippine government and the IMF, the
Manila Standard newspaper said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the memorandum set conditions for the
country's 1.8 billion dollar standby credit arrangement with the
IMF.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, the Philippine government will eliminate
the volatility band entirely soon to "improve the function of the
interbank foreign exchange market."
</P>
<P>
The Bankers Association of the Philippines (BAP), the owner and
operator of the Philippines' electronic foreign exchange market,
already expressed openness to the proposal, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the allowable daily fluctuation of the peso against
the dollar at the foreign exchange market has been placed at six
percent of the weighted afternoon average of the previous day.
</P>
<P>
The volatility band was first introduced in 1994 to shield the
local currency from wild market swings. The band was scrapped
after the central bank devalued the peso last July, but was
re-imposed last October to prevent the fast depreciation of the
local currency.
</P>
<P>
BAP earlier opposed moves to lift the band, saying it has been
serving its purpose given the abnormal market conditions.
</P>
<P>
During the past month, the Philippine currency has appreciated
from 45 pesos against the dollar to 40 pesos to the greenback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
