<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Banking Reforms Underway, Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Banking reforms are now in full
swing in East Asia, where many banks, besieged with increasing
non-performing loans or huge debts, are struggling for their
survival.
</P>
<P>
The reform process started eight months ago, when the region
was hit by a financial crisis, the worst in more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
During the past months, South Korea, Thailand, Indonesia,
Malaysia and the Philippines have taken drastic measures to reform
their banking sector, including take-overs, forced closures and
mergers of troubled banks.
</P>
<P>
However, problems in the banking sector are so deep that the
on-going reforms are expected to meet formidable challenges,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
No doubt, the banking sector has played a very important role
in East Asia's fast economic growth in the last two decades. But
mis-management and poor banking regulations in some countries have
resulted in a mountain of non-performing loans and foreign debts,
threatening the normal operation of the banking system.
</P>
<P>
In most of Southeast Asian countries and South Korea,
non-performing loans accounted for around 20 percent of total bank
loans, and East Asian banks, excluding Japanese banks, have owed
171 billion US dollars to international banks by last July.
</P>
<P>
As the eight-month-old financial crisis is still lingering in
the region, the situation in the banking sector may get even worse
this year with the rising of bad loans.
</P>
<P>
In Indonesia, analysts said, bad bank loans may rise to more
than 25 percent of total lending by 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the course of the banking reforms, East Asian countries have
closed or taken over some banks whose liabilities far outweighed
their assets to prevent new financial risks.
</P>
<P>
Following Indonesia's closure of 16 commercial banks and
Thailand's 56 financial firms last year, South Korea shut 10
merchant banks in January.
</P>
<P>
In February, the Thai central bank seized control of two
mid-sized banks, First Bangkok City Bank PCL, and Siam City Bank
PCL, leaving five of the country's 15 banks under government
ownership.
</P>
<P>
As banks are pillars of national economies, East Asian
governments cannot close all banks in trouble and have to bail out
most of them.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said, the bailout has proved costly and would
become a heavy financial burden for governments.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand said last week that it has spent 25.46
billion dollars since Mid-1996 to prop up troubled financial
institutions, but a large proportion of that money is expected to
be unrecoverable.
</P>
<P>
By secretly spending an amount greater than last year's
government budget to keep the Thai financial system afloat, the
central bank drained the nation's resources. New tax increases
will be necessary to pay for the lending, analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
Some economists said that unless the governments inject public
money into the financial system, Indonesia, Korea and Thailand
will face the prospect of a prolonged credit crunch, tight
liquidity, bank runs and lack of confidence in the banking system.
</P>
<P>
Realizing the weakness of the banking system, East Asian
governments have ordered bank recapitalizations to consolidate the
banking sector either though mergers or injection of new financial
resources.
</P>
<P>
In Indonesia, five private banks merged into one in January
with new assets of 5.9 billion dollars. By June this year, 50
banks in the country are expected to be merged into 12 banks,
banking sources said. In Malaysia, 40 financial companies were
ordered to merge with each other and the merger deals must be
finalized by March 31.
</P>
<P>
But the recapitalization also needs government support and the
bill is huge, economists said. They estimated that the
recapitalization plan will cost Thailand 15 billion to 25 billion
dollars, and South Korea 34 billion to 54 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
As part of the banking reforms and a way of seeking financial
resources to enhance the sector, Thailand has recently revoked
laws barring foreigners from owing majority stakes in banks, and
foreign investors can now buy majority voting shares in its 91
financial companies, including the 56 closed last December, and 15
commercial banks. Indonesia has also decided to allow 100 percent
foreign ownership of its banks.
</P>
<P>
All these reform moves taken by East Asian countries will
surely help put their house in order, but the recovery of the
banking sector may take several years because of the scale of
problems, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
