<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Encourages More Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Governments of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) have agreed to relax the entry
regulations in the ASEAN Industrial Cooperation (AICO) scheme to
allow the entry of prospective foreign investors in ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Bulletin newspaper Saturday quoted Melito Salazar,
Philippines' trade and industry under-secretary, as saying that
the entry rule was relaxed last week after ASEAN members adopted a
pre-investment approval scheme at the request of the United States
ASEAN Business Council.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the AICO scheme only allows the participation of firms
already operating and organized in ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
But now, Salazar said, a prospective ASEAN investor or a
foreign company planning to invest in ASEAN can apply for an AICO
arrangement in advance subject to certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
These conditions include a one-year time frame in which the
prospective investor is expected to file his application for the
AICO project, he said.
</P>
<P>
Salazar said that at present only 15 applications for the
region are being processed with only Volvo and Sunden Corp.
receiving green light.
</P>
<P>
Volvo plans to establish an assembly plant in Thailand, while
information technology company Sunden Corp. wants to set a base in
Thailand and Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
