<HEADLINE> Drought Kills Cattle in Amazonian Zone of Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A protracted drought in the
Amazonian region of Brazil has killed thousands of cattle,
Brazilian official sources said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the drought has also caused water supply
problems to the population of several places in the state of
Roraima, in the north of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The Roraima state Agriculture Ministry reported that the state
has already registered the death of 12,000 heads of cattle because
of the longest ever drought in the Amazonian region.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said 300 to 400 heads of cattle die every day of
thirst and hunger.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian state of Roraima, bordering Venezuela, has a herd
of approximately 400,000 heads of cattle.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the inhabitants of the Paracaima
municipality, about 220 kilometers from the city of Boa Vista, the
capital of the state, are supplied by tank trucks with water
brought from Santa Elena de Uairen, in the south of Venezuela.
enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
