<HEADLINE> Ukraine, US Sign Accord on Nuclear Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine and the U.S. signed an accord
on satellite technology and initialed an agreement on peaceful
nuclear cooperation here Friday.
</P>
<P>
On her one-day working visit to Kiev, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright met with Ukrainian Foreign Minister Gennady
Udovenko and President Leonid Kuchma.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after the meeting, Albright commended
Ukraine's decision to cancel a deal to provide turbines to an
Iranian nuclear power station in Bushehr. She pledged support for
Ukraine's plan to join an international agreement to curb the
spread of missile technology.
</P>
<P>
President Kuchma said at a news conference that membership in
the Missile Technology Control Regime would pave the way for
Ukraine's participation in the international space technology
market.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said the Ukraine has no intention of selling its
strategic and tactical missiles.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Udovenko hoped the nuclear cooperation
agreement would help Ukraine attract more U.S. investment and
improve the development of its nuclear industry.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Secretary of State promised Ukraine new and safe
nuclear fuels.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said Albright's visit was made soon after
Kuchma's first official visit to Russia. Ukrainian-Russian
relations have been improving. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
