<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based Newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Deputies to the ongoing First Session of the National
People's Congress heard three reports on government's work
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Top of yesterday's agenda was State Councillor Luo Gan's report
on the central government's institutional restructuring plan.
</P>
<P>
The two other documents are the report by Minister of the State
Planning Commission Chen Jinhua on implementation of the 1997
economic and social development plan and the draft 1998 plan, and
the report by Minister of Finance Liu Zhongli on implementation of
the 1997 central and local government budgets and draft 1998
budgets.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin yesterday stressed the importance of
viewing the Southeast Asian financial turmoil from a proper
perspective. He also called for looking after laid-off workers of
the state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng yesterday stressed the importance of
agriculture, the reform of state-owned enterprises and the
wellbeing of laid-off workers during a panel discussion of the
First Session of the Ninth NPC.
</P>
<P>
"Agriculture should be given priority in economic work,"
because a large proportion of the population in north China's
Hebei Province is engaged in agriculture, Li Peng told the NPC
deputies from the province.
</P>
<P>
-- Hu Jintao, member of the Standing Committee of the CPC
Political Bureau, stressed at a panel discussion of the First
Session of the Ninth NPC that the development of Tibet requires
stability while stability will be good for development.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China's legislative body heard yesterday of a bold plan to
shake up the State Council by axing 11 ministries and slashing the
number of government officials by half.
</P>
<P>
Next week, deputies will examine the plan to reduce the number
of ministries from 40 to 29.
</P>
<P>
-- While keeping a tight fiscal policy in place, China plans to
increase investment in fixed assest by 10 percent to guarantee an
eight percent economic growth rate, said Chen Jinhua, Minister of
the State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
-- China will pare its budget deficit by 9.506 billion yuan
(1.15 billion US dollars) this year despite growing financial
demands from agriculture and unemployment, Finance Minister Liu
Zhongli said yesterday.  
</P>
