<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Pudong Looking for Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The Pudong New Area in China's
Shanghai has worked out methods to get more investment to fill the
gap in capital in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Pudong expects to need 240 billion yuan by the year 2000, but
only 180 billion yuan has been made sure, leaving a gap of 60
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The new measures will decrease the price of land and houses in
the area to help investors hold down production costs. Large
projects and high-tech projects will be the first beneficiaries of
the measure.
</P>
<P>
Unreasonable fees will also be stopped with more stringent
supervision.
</P>
<P>
Domestic companies from other parts of the country that have
not enjoyed the same policies as their Shanghai counterparts in
loans and foreign trade, will be encourage to settle in the area,
which promises to solve these problems one by one.
</P>
<P>
After seven years of work, the Pudong New Area has taken shape
in Shanghai, and 4,900 foreign-funded projects have been approved,
backed by 15 billion US dollars of contractual foreign
investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
