<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Has Nearly 1,000 Commodity Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of commodity markets
in Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province, had
reached 953 by the end of 1997, of which 748 are in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
This means there is a commodity market for every 6,000 people
in the province.
</P>
<P>
The markets can be divided into four specialized fields. Of the
total, 130 are comprehensive consumers' markets, 361 are for farm
and agriculture-related products, 376 for manufactured consumers'
goods, and 81 for production means.
</P>
<P>
There are 29 markets with an annual turnover of more than 100
million yuan each.
</P>
<P>
The markets registered a total of 31.4 billion yuan in business
turnover last year, up 18 percent over 1996 and accounting for 39
percent of the consumer retail sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Train Derailing Killed Ten, Injured Thirty-six in Finland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Ten people were killed and 36
seriously injured on Friday when a train derailed in central
Finland, the worst train crash in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
The train from Turku to Pieksamaki was thrown off the tracks as
it approached a station in the town of Jyvaskyla, 270 kilometers
north of Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
The train carrying about 500 passengers and running behind
schedule went too fast and did not reduce the speed while entering
the station, a survivor said.
</P>
<P>
The search of the black box on the train was difficult
because of the heavy snow.
</P>
<P>
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari and the Finnish government
sent messages of condolence to the families of the victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
