<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Inland River Shipping Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- China had 111,000 km of inland
waterways by 1997, with 50 deepwater berths, and 260,000 boats
handling 22 million tons of goods.
</P>
<P>
In the last two years, about 1,740 kilometers of inland
waterways were improved, 31 major berths added, and handling
capacity increased by 10.95 million tons, while 850 million tons
of goods were shipped in 1997, 16.4 percent more than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
A supervisory system was established on the Suzhou river, a
part of the Sunan Canal in Jiangsu Province, for the first time in
the construction history of China's canals.
</P>
<P>
China has also put more money into inland waterway
construction, and the Ministry of Communications has set up an
inland waterway shipping fund, while central and local governments
have spent 6.13 billion yuan on it for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
China will construct 20 waterways with a total length of 15,000
km, along with berths and guarantee facilities. The state will
make all key inland waterways navigable in 30 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
