<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, March 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS -- Trevor Rees-Jones, the bodyguard of late Princess
Diana, revealed nothing new during Friday's hearing with French
judge Herve Stephan.
</P>
<P>
Rees-Jones only confirmed what he told the British tabloid
"Mirror" a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
His latest memory about the crash in the mid-night of August
31, 1997, in the Alma tunnel is that the Mercedes which was
carrying Diana, Dodi Al-Fayed and himself was pursued by two cars
and one motorcycle after they left the Hotel Ritz, and that Diana
called the name of Dodi after the crash.
</P>
<P>
But he told the judge that memory about the crash was coming
back to him little by little. (Diana-Judge-Hearing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai Friday
launched a new appeal to Syria for the resumption of dialogue and
again expressed Israel's readiness to withdraw from southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to meet the Syrians around the negotiation table and
find the means to solve this conflict which has last already 50
years," said Mordechai after a meeting with his French counterpart
Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Israel is seeking to re-establish peace and
security in southern Lebanon and to let Lebanese resume control of
that part of territory, in order to "prevent the threat of
terrorism from weighing on Israeli citizens."
</P>
<P>
But he said that Israel has no choice but to stay in southern
Lebanon and "make order reign" if the threats from terrorism are
not removed. (Israel-Syria-Dialogue)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Deputy
Secretary-General Louise Frechette Friday urged women to recommit
themselves to ensure that equal rights of men and women as
enshrined in the United Nations Charter become a reality.
</P>
<P>
Opening a panel discussion at the United Nations headquarters
commemorating International Women's Day, Ms. Frechette said that
the movement of women's rights was one of the momentous in the
history of humankind. (U.N.-Women's Rights)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Jayantha Dhanapala, head of U.N. Special
Group for inspections of Presidential Sites in Iraq, will travel
to Baghdad Monday to prepare for the Group's inspection activities
there, it was announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The detailed inspection procedures have been finalized and they
will be presented to the U.N. Security Council Monday, spokesman
for U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Group was set up under the agreement reached between Annan
and Iraq on February 23 during Annan's trip to Baghdad to solve
the crisis over U.N. arms inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said an inspection team led by
American Scott Ritter resumed inspections in Iraq Friday. They
viewed three sites which were all declared sensitive by Iraq, he
added. (U.N.-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The sanctions against Libya for its failure
to turn over the two men accused of bombing an Pan American
airliner in 1988 will remain in place, Bill Richardson, the
Ambassador of the United States to the United Nations said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Richardson made the remarks after the united Nations Security
Council finished its informal consultations on the issue of Libya.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said the sanctions will remain in place until there
is compliance by Libya with the will of the international
community and hand out the two suspected men.
</P>
<P>
Libya has been under sanctions since 1992 for failing to hand
over two suspects in the 1988 mid-air bombing of a Pan American
airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, which killed 270 people.
(U.S.-Libya) 
</P>
</TEXT>
