<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Awaits Word on Temple of Heaven's Inclusion on UNESCO List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The Temple of Heaven, considered
China's largest and best-preserved royal family altar, has
retained its style and ancient charm because of the Chinese
government's efforts to protect the historic site.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has officially applied to the United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO)
for the altar's inclusion on its World Heritage List.
</P>
<P>
Located in the southern part of Beijing, the Temple of Heaven
used to serve as a place for the emperors of the Ming (1368-1644)
and Qing (1644-1911) dynasties to worship heaven and pray for a
good harvest.
</P>
<P>
Worshiping Heaven, a traditional rite to offer sacrifices to
heaven, was conducted by Chinese emperors to consolidate their
rein, because they regarded themselves as sons of heaven.
</P>
<P>
The sacrifices were abolished by the government of the Republic
of China. The Temple of Heaven became a historic site and was
opened to the public as a park in 1918.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949,
ancient structures in the Temple of Heaven have all received
additional protection. The State Council listed the temple as a
historic place of interest under state protection in 1961.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Beijing municipal government has allocated
special funds for maintenance of the temple on many occasions.
</P>
<P>
Xu Zhichang, a senior engineer with the Temple of Heaven, said
the temple contains ideology on traditional Chinese morphology,
and represents the highest level of construction for a sacrificial
altar in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
The name, location, overall arrangements, design and color of
the Temple of Heaven all reflect the understanding and aesthetic
conceptions of the Chinese nation accumulated for 1,000 years, Xu
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong Province To Build Energy-Storing Power Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 7 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province plans
to invest 5.5 billion yuan (about 670 million US dollars) to
construct a large energy efficient power station in the scenic
Mount Taishan Valley.
</P>
<P>
The plant, which will feature four turbogenerator units rated
at 200,000 kw each, is designed to use excess energy by pumping
water from the lower to the upper reservoir. Excess water stored
in the upper reservoir will flow through turbines to the lower
reservoir to generate ample power when needed.
</P>
<P>
Shandong currently has a total generating capacity of 16.5
million kw, with the gap between peak and low demand standing at
four million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
Heavy losses result from the fact that generating units have to
be deactivated during periods of low demand. However, the new
energy efficient station is designed to ensure the overall
operation of the local power network.
</P>
<P>
Shandong currently ranks second amongst the nation's provinces
in terms of power generation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Expected To Be Largest Construction Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai will become the largest
construction market in Asia and even in the world within a few
years, experts predict.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's rate of investment has increased rapidly in recent
years, with investment in fixed assets totaling more than 390
billion yuan in the 1991-1995 period, more than three times the
figure for the 1986-1990 period, experts said in a research report.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will invest another 1.6 trillion yuan in fixed assets
during the 1996-2000 period, triple the previous five years,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Based on these calculations, Shanghai would be the largest
construction market in Asia and even in the world.
</P>
<P>
Urban transportation-related infrastructure construction will
be a major part of the market. Major projects include the subway
system, ring roads, cross-river projects, an international airport
and deep-water harbors.
</P>
<P>
Housing is another boom area of the Shanghai construction
market, as the municipality plans to build 50 million square
meters of housing in the 1996-2000 period, with total investment
estimated at more than 150 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Investment in renovating the inner city and developing tourism
as well as commercial and cultural facilities will also be great,
the experts said.
</P>
<P>
They added that the construction market will be bolstered by
industrial restructuring, technical renovation, relocating
factories away from the downtown area and the development of
high-technology industries and new industrial parks.
</P>
<P>
The Pudong New Area, a rising finance and trade zone separated
from downtown Shanghai by the Huangpujiang River, is expected to
contribute a great deal to the boom, as its construction
investment accounts for 30 percent of the municipality's total.
</P>
<P>
The experts said that the Shanghai construction market is so
huge that competition will increase among domestic and foreign
construction companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
