<DOCNO> XIE19980307.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Commissioner Urges More Female Workforce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Member states of the European
Union (EU) must take necessary steps to boost women's employment
and address the reasons behind higher women's unemployment, an EU
official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Padraig Flynn, European commissioner for employment and social
affairs, made the remark Friday in Brussels at a celebration of
International Women's Day which falls on March 8.
</P>
<P>
He said that women had accounted for the entire growth of the
EU's workforce over the last 10 to 15 years and their employment
had risen from only 54 percent of that of men in 1975 to over 70
percent at present.
</P>
<P>
"If we think about how Europe's working population is set to
diminish in the near future as the greying of the population takes
place, we begin to see just how important women's participation is
to our future prosperity," said the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the Jobs Summit, which was held in Luxembourg
in November 1997, and its Employment Guidelines had set a clear
policy line of promoting equal opportunities.
</P>
<P>
He urged the 15 member states to take necessary measures to
increase the employment rate of EU women and to investigate the
reasons for higher women's unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"They have signed up to do more about reconciling work and
family life. They have agreed to raise the level of care
provision. They are committed to addressing the particular
problems faced by women returning to work after an absence," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the theme of the 1998 Women's Day, the campaign in
favor of the women in Kabul, Flynn said, "The denial of the human
rights of Afghan women and girls is absolute and it is appalling."
</P>
<P>
"The brave Afghan women who have sought to oppose and highlight
injustice deserve all our support. We must make their cause our
cause," the commissioner said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
