<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Presses for More Funds to Troops in Bosnia, Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen pressed the administration's case Friday for 1.85
billion U.S. dollars in emergency money to help maintain U.S.
forces in both the Gulf and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
However, testifying before the Senate Appropriation Committee,
Cohen and General Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, ran into congressional skepticism over the price and
duration of both missions.
</P>
<P>
Senator Robert Byrd of West Virginia, the senior Democrat in
the committee, complained of what he called an "open-ended"
operation in Bosnia and a do-it-alone strategy in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Byrd criticized the administration for telling Congress the
troops would be home by June 30, and then breaking its promise.
"To put it charitably, the administration was being very
disingenuous," Byrd said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen told the committee there were now about 34,000 U.S.
troops in the Gulf, most of them on ships. "We intend to keep that
level of force there as long as necessary," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
On Bosnia, Cohen conceded that the administration would not be
able to bring troops home by June 1 as it had earlier promised.
</P>
<P>
"It's hard to fix an end date as such," he said. However, he
said that U.S. troops in Bosnia would be reduced from the current
8,500 to about 6,900.
</P>
<P>
He noted that many positive things had been achieved in Bosnia,
including an improving economy, the surrender of indicted war
criminals, the return of refugees and a reduction of rival
soldiers in the field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
