<HEADLINE> Clinton Expresses Support for Shevardnadze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
called Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze on Friday to express
his support and to reaffirm U.S. hopes for a peaceful settlement
in the Black Sea province of Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders spoke for about 20 minutes, White House
spokesman Mike McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
"The president wanted to express his personal and strong
support for President Shevardnadze, especially in light of some of
the recent events that President Shevardnadze has encountered,"
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
On February 25, four U.N. military observers were released
unharmed several days after they were kidnaped by a group which
was demanding the release of seven comrades jailed for
assassination attempt against Shevardnadze.
</P>
<P>
U.N. observers are in Georgia to monitor a truce between
government forces and separatists in Abkhazia. They helped prevent
further outbreaks of fighting, but progress toward a political
settlement has been slow.  
</P>
