<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Spending Sets Record in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Election
Commission (FEC) Friday said that candidates in the 1998
congressional elections raised a total of 233 million dollars for
their campaigns, making last year the priciest off-year election
season in history.
</P>
<P>
In a fundraising analysis released Friday, the FEC found
candidates raised 26 percent more money than during the 1996
elections. The 1,037 congressional candidates spent a total of 112
million dollars on their campaigns in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Senate candidates raised 98 million dollars and spent 38.9
million dollars. Candidates for the House of Representatives
raised 136 million dollars and spent 73 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The study shows fundraising levels jumped sharply in elections
in both chambers.
</P>
<P>
More than half the campaign contributions came in the form of
individual donations, while political action committees of various
interest groups donated a total of 63 million dollars. Candidates
also spent or borrowed 19 million of their own money for their
campaigns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
