<HEADLINE> Diana's Bodyguard Reveals Nothing New to French Judge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Trevor Rees-Jones, the bodyguard of
late Princess Diana, revealed nothing new during Friday's hearing
with French judge Herve Stephan.
</P>
<P>
Rees-Jones only confirmed what he told the British tabloid
"Mirror" a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
His latest memory about the crash in the mid-night of August
31, 1997, in the Alma tunnel is that the Mercedes which was
carrying Diana, Dodi Al-Fayed and himself was pursued by two cars
and one motorcycle after they left the Hotel Ritz, and that Diana
called the name of Dodi after the crash.
</P>
<P>
But he told the judge that memory about the crash was coming
back to him little by little.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer of Rees-Jones, Christian Curtil, said after the
one-hour hearing at the Palace of Justice in Paris that his client
confirmed the content of the interview published by "the Mirror"",
although it was not he himself who sought to publish the story.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to Rees-Jones said the British embassy in Paris
was in charge of the security of Rees-Jones when he travelled this
time from London to have the hearing, the fourth summoned by judge
Herve Stephan.
</P>
<P>
When he had his last hearing in Paris in December, Rees-Jones
was protected by the Hotel Ritz, owned by the Al-Fayed family.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Al-Fayed, the father of Dodi Al-Fayed, told the British
press recently that he was almost sure that Diana was killed in a
conspiracy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
