<HEADLINE> Blair Defends Economic Policy, Welfare Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said on Friday his Labor party is both the "party of economic
competence and the defender of the welfare state."
</P>
<P>
In his speech to Labor's Scottish conference, Blair said
economic strength was the key to securing a second term.
</P>
<P>
The message comes less than a fortnight before what Blair said
would be a "Budget of confidence".
</P>
<P>
"It will push forward reform of the welfare state by the
promotion of work and independence because New Labor, not the
Tories is the party of enterprise today," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the country now has the best chance for generations to
secure real long-term economic strength. "But it can't be done
unless we take a tight grip on public spending, unless we take
tough decisions needed to secure stability and compete with the
rest of the world. "
</P>
<P>
Blair said sound economics did not have to compete with his
party's obligation to fund the benefits and health system.
</P>
<P>
"We are the party of the welfare state," he said. "I will never
turn my back on the sick, disabled and those unable to look after
themselves."
</P>
<P>
He repeated his case for thorough reform of the system to get
the support to people most in need.
</P>
<P>
"The true mark of obligation to the welfare state lies in the
absolute commitment to ensuring that, from generation to
generation, it is able to serve those who need it more
effectively. That is our commitment," he added.  
</P>
