<HEADLINE> European Shares End Week Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
recovered from recent losses and ended the week higher, with Paris
hitting a new record closing high, boosted by a strong opening on
Wall Street, dollar's strength and new merger talks.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index of leading shares closed sharply
higher after falling for three consecutive sessions, lifted by a
new bout of takeover rumors in the pharmaceuticals sector and a
rebound among financial stocks. The FTSE 100 closed at 5,782.9, up
87.3 points, or 1.53 percent, a gain of 15.6 points on last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market shrugged off
stronger-than-expected U.S. February jobs figures and a
first-quarter profit warning from semiconductor and
telecommunications group Motorola.
</P>
<P>
Renewed merger speculation saw shares in Glaxo and SmithKline
rally 2.1 percent and 3.6 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt also ended sharply higher on the
back of the strong U.S. dollar and an upturn in the chemical
sector, but off the day's best levels, still holding below the
4,800-point level as traders said more gains were to come in the
weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index closed at 4715.95, up 92.55 points, or 2.00
percent, 6.12 points higher on the week.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, The CAC-40 index rallied thanks to stronger
international markets and buoyant banking shares, finishing the
week 87.42 points or 2.57 percent up at 3,483.22, a rise of 61.3
points last Friday, and a new closing record.  
</P>
