<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Defense Minister Invites Syria to Resume Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai Friday launched a new appeal to Syria for the resumption
of dialogue and again expressed Israel's readiness to withdraw
from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to meet the Syrians around the negotiation table and
find the means to solve this conflict which has last already 50
years," said Mordechai after a meeting with his French counterpart
Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Israel is seeking to re-establish peace and
security in southern Lebanon and to let Lebanese resume control of
that part of territory, in order to "prevent the threat of
terrorism from weighing on Israeli citizens."
</P>
<P>
"When the Lebanese army and government could guarantee the
security in southern Lebanon, we could implement the Resolution
425 of the U.N. Security Council in such a way as envisaging a
redeployment of Israeli troops," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he said that Israel has no choice but to stay in southern
Lebanon and "make order reign" if the threats from terrorism are
not removed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
